year=2015 |website=Amazon}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | United Kingdom\n| March 4, 2016\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Phonograph record|Vinyl]]\n| [[Decca Records|Decca]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Traveller-VINYL-Chris-Stapleton/dp/B00UI23YDU/ref=sr_1_4?s=music&ie=UTF8&qid=1494560575&sr=1-4&keywords=chris+stapleton |title=Traveller [VINYL] |year=2016 |website=Amazon}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | United States\n| May 26, 2015\n| Mercury Nashville\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Traveller-2-LP-Chris-Stapleton/dp/B00UI23YDU/ref=pd_sim_15_1?_encoding=UTF8&pd_rd_i=B00UI23YDU&pd_rd_r=66KZ3ERBZVK7NV6S5SHS&pd_rd_w=72Dmv&pd_rd_wg=CoSIx&psc=1&refRID=66KZ3ERBZVK7NV6S5SHS |title=Traveller [2 LP] |year=2015 |website=Amazon}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Discogs master|845230|type=album|Traveller}}\n*{{Youtube|ZI-aPHeUDlk|\"Fire Away\"}}\n\n{{Chris Stapleton}}\n\n[[Category:2015 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Chris Stapleton albums]]\n[[Category:Mercury Nashville albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Dave Cobb]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Best Country Album]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Traveller\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Chris Stapleton]]\n| cover      = Traveller (Chris Stapleton album).jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2015|05|05}}\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[RCA Studio A]], Blackbird Studios in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]]\n| genre      =\n* [[Country music|Country]]\n* [[Rock music|rock]]\n* [[country rock]]\n* [[Southern rock]]\n* [[Soul music|soul]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=63|s=04}}\n| label      = [[Universal Music Group Nashville|Mercury Nashville]]\n| producer   =\n* [[Dave Cobb]]\n* Stapleton\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[From A Room: Volume 1]]\n| next_year  = 2017\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Traveller\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Traveller (song)|Traveller]]\n | single1date = April 27, 2015\n | single2     = [[Nobody to Blame]]\n | single2date = November 9, 2015\n | single3     = [[Parachute (song)|Parachute]]\n | single3date = May 2, 2016<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.countryaircheck.com/pdf_publication/Issue_495%20-%20April%2018,%202016.pdf|title=Country Aircheck Issue 495  |work=Country Aircheck|date=April 18, 2016 |accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n'''''Traveller''''' is the debut studio album by American singer-songwriter [[Chris Stapleton]]. The album was produced by [[Dave Cobb]] and Stapleton, and was released on May 5, 2015, through [[Universal Music Group Nashville|Mercury Nashville]].\n\nDescribed by music publications as an old-school country, [[Southern rock]] record, ''Traveller'' received critical acclaim and earned Stapleton several awards. It was named [[Country Music Association Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] at the [[49th Annual Country Music Association Awards|2015 Country Music Association Awards]]. Furthermore, it received a nomination at the [[58th Annual Grammy Awards|58th Grammy Awards]] for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] and a win for [[Grammy Award for Best Country Album|Best Country Album]]. The song \"[[Traveller (song)|Traveller]]\" also won [[Grammy Award for Best Country Solo Performance|Best Country Solo Performance]]. At the [[51st Academy of Country Music Awards|2016 Academy of Country Music Awards]] it won Album of the Year, with the song \"[[Nobody to Blame]]\" also winning Song of the Year. It won the [[Billboard Music Award]] for [[Billboard Music Award for Top Country Album|Top Country Album]] in 2016 and 2017.\n\n''Traveller'' reached number one on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart after a duet performance by Stapleton and [[Justin Timberlake]] at the 2015 Country Music Association Awards. The album has been certified quadruple platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) and has sold over 2.6 million copies in the United States by November 2019.<ref name=\"sales\"/> It generated three singles: \"[[Traveller (Chris Stapleton song)|Traveller]]\", \"[[Nobody to Blame]]\", and \"[[Parachute (Chris Stapleton song)|Parachute]]\". \"Nobody to Blame\" reached the top 10 on the [[Country Airplay]] chart.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7300643/billboard-charts-march-25-chris-stapleton-troye-sivan-madonna | title=13 Things to Know About the Billboard Charts This Week: Chris Stapleton Scores First Top 10 Hit & More | work=Billboard | date=March 26, 2016 | accessdate=March 26, 2016 | author=Greenwald, Morgan}}</ref> The album track \"[[Fire Away (song)|Fire Away]]\" was accompanied by a music video.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/see-chris-stapletons-harrowing-fire-away-video-20160229 | title=See Chris Stapleton's Harrowing 'Fire Away' Video | work=Rolling Stone | date=February 29, 2016 | accessdate=February 29, 2016 | author=Freeman, Jon}}</ref>\n\n==Music and composition==\n{{Quote box\n |quote =  I lost my dad in October 2013 and did a little bit of soul-searching. My wife was kind enough to buy me an old Jeep. We flew out to Phoenix and drove it all the way back to Nashville through the desert. I thought a lot about music and my dad, and the things that he would have liked that I should be doing. Out of that, I actually wrote the song 'Traveller' driving down Interstate 40 through New Mexico. That became the cornerstone for the record and wound up being the title track. \n |source =&nbsp;\u2014 Stapleton speaking about his inspiration for the album during an interview with ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-615/6553503/chris-stapleton-debut-album-traveller-interview | title=Chris Stapleton's Debut Album 'Traveller' Inspired by 'Soul-Searching' Road Trip | publisher=Prometheus Global Media | work=Billboard | date=April 30, 2015 | accessdate=November 15, 2015 | author=Dauphin, Chuck}}</ref>\n |quoted = true\n |bgcolor = #FFFFF0\n |align = right\n |width = 28%\n |border = 1px\n |fontsize = 90%\n}}\nThe album is an old-school country record mixed with [[Southern rock]]. Tracks on the album features electric guitar, mandolin, and acoustic guitar. \"The Devil Named Music\" exclaims the hard life on the road, while \"Might As Well Get Stoned\" features resignation lyrics.<ref name=\"y1978\"/> Musically, \"Sometimes I Cry\" is a blues song,<ref name=\"y1978\">{{cite web | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/chris-stapleton-on-why-stunning-new-album-traveller-isnt-for-kids-20150507 | title=Chris Stapleton on Why Stunning New Album 'Traveller' Isn't for Kids | work=Roling Stone | date=May 7, 2015 | accessdate=November 15, 2015}}</ref> \"[[Nobody to Blame]]\" a mid-tempo [[country rock]] track,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/music/chris-stapleton-brings-back-introspective-old-school-country-music/ |title=Chris Stapleton brings back introspective, old-school country music |last=Smit |first=Owen R. |date=March 23, 2017 |work=The Seattle Times |access-date=April 15, 2017}}</ref> and \"[[Fire Away (song)|Fire Away]]\" features a beat in a classic soul-ballad time signature.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/6554078/chris-stapleton-nyc-release-party-concert |title=Chris Stapleton Shows His Inner Stax Soul Man at Album Release Party In New York: Live Review |last=Leight |first=Elias |date=May 6, 2016 |work=Billboard |access-date=April 30, 2017}}</ref> \"Daddy Doesn't Pray Anymore\" shrouds reflections about his father in the language of religious backsliding and was previously covered by [[Julie Roberts]] in 2013.<ref name=\"bb\"/> In an interview for ''Rolling Stone'', Stapleton commented \"If somebody tells me it sounds dated, I'd say that's great, as long as the date is 1978. My favorite things are from then.\"<ref name=\"y1978\"/>\n\nStapleton wrote or co-wrote all but two of the album's 14 tracks. The album features a blues-influenced cover of [[David Allan Coe]]'s single \"[[Tennessee Whiskey (song)|Tennessee Whiskey]]\", and [[Charlie Daniels]]' \"Was It 26,\" written by Don Sampson.<ref name=\"y1978\"/>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nThe album debuted on the Top Country Albums chart at number two, and the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] at number 14, selling 27,000 copies in the week ending May 10.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6561560/chris-stapleton-best-sales-new-country-artist |title=Chris Stapleton Starts With Best Sales for a New Country Artist in 2015|author= Keith Caulfield and Gary Trust |date= May 14, 2015 | work=Billboard}}</ref>\n\nSix months after the album was released, Chris Stapleton and [[Justin Timberlake]] performed \"[[Tennessee Whiskey (song)|Tennessee Whiskey]]\" at the [[49th Annual Country Music Association Awards|2015 Country Music Association Awards]] where ''Traveller'' won [[Country Music Association Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/see-chris-stapleton-and-justin-timberlakes-stunning-cma-awards-duet-20151104|title=See Chris Stapleton and Justin Timberlake's Stunning CMA Awards Duet|author= Marissa R. Moss |date=November 4, 2015|work=Rolling Stone }}</ref> Following the performance, sales for the album increased 6,000%<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nielsen.com/content/dam/corporate/us/en/reports-downloads/2016-reports/2015-year-end-music-report.pdf.pdf | title=2015 Nielsen Music U.S. Report | publisher=Nielsen | date=January 6, 2016 | accessdate=January 6, 2016}}</ref> and it re-entered the ''Billboard'' 200 at number one after being absent from the chart since September, with 177,000 equivalent album units (153,000 in pure album sales). According to ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', the surge in sales is owed to how a mass audience discovered Stapleton on the November 4 CMA Awards broadcast. ''Traveller'' is also the first debut country album to reach number one on the ''Billboard'' 200 in over four years, with ''[[Clear as Day]]'' (2011) by [[Scotty McCreery]] being the last.<ref name=\"bb200\">{{cite news|last1=Caulfield|first1=Keith|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6754084/chris-stapleton-soars-to-no-1-on-billboard-200-albums-chart | title=Chris Stapleton Soars to No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart After CMAs | publisher=Prometheus Global Media | work=Billboard | date=November 8, 2015 | accessdate=November 9, 2015}}</ref> It became the first album to reenter the chart at number one. It remained at number one for a second week with 124,000 [[album-equivalent unit]]s, including 97,000 pure album sales.<ref name=\"secweek\">{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6762538/chris-stapleton-tops-billboard-200-second-week | title=Chris Stapleton Spends Second Week at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart | publisher=Prometheus Global Media | work=Billboard | date=November 15, 2015 | accessdate=November 15, 2015 | author=Caulfield, Keith}}</ref> The album track \"[[Tennessee Whiskey (song)|Tennessee Whiskey]]\" topped the [[Hot Country Songs]] chart,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6760622/chris-stapleton-country-music-charts-radio |title=Chris Stapleton Travels to Top of Country Charts Without Strong Support From Radio |last=Asker |first=Jim |date=November 10, 2015 |work=Billboard |access-date=April 15, 2017}}</ref> and reached the top 20 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].\n\nThe album sold 685,000 copies in the United States in 2015.<ref name=\"us sales\"/> In February 2016, ''Traveller'' was certified platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), and double platinum in September.<ref name=\"riaa\"/> It became the fourth best-selling album of 2016 in the nation, and the top selling country album, with 1.04 million copies sold that year.<ref name=\"us sales\">{{cite web |url=https://www.yahoo.com/music/top-15-albums-2016-slideshow-wp-000902015/photo-p-album-sold-1-042-photo-000902241.html |title=The Top-Selling Albums of 2016 |work=Yahoo Music! |first=Paul |last= Grein|date=December 20, 2016 }}</ref> The album surpassed the 2 million sales mark in the US in July 2017,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7865966/billboard-200-chart-moves-chris-stapletons-traveller |title=Billboard 200 Chart Moves: Chris Stapleton's 'Traveller' Surpasses 2 Million in U.S. Sales |date=July 14, 2017 |first= Keith |last=Caulfield|work=Billboard }}</ref>, and it was the second best-selling country album of 2017 (after Stapleton's second album ''[[From A Room: Volume 1]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/money/2018/01/04/country-musics-most-listened-artists-chris-stapleton-luke-bryan-thomas-rhett-2017/1003648001/ |title=Revealed: Country music's most listened to artists in 2017 |first=Nate|last= Rau |work=Tennessean |publisher=USA Today |date= January 4, 2018 }}</ref> It hold the records for the most weeks atop the [[Americana/Folk Albums]] chart (81 in total as of August 2019).<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8254686/chris-stapleton-first-country-airplay-no-1-broken-halos |title=Chris Stapleton Claims First Country Airplay Leader With 'Broken Halos' |last=Asker |first=Jim |date=March 20, 2018 |work=Billboard |access-date=March 20, 2018}}</ref> It topped the [[Billboard Year-End|''Billboard'' Year-End]] Top Country Albums chart in 2016 and 2017.<ref name=\"year end 2016\"/><ref name=\"year end 2017\"/> It was certified quadruple platinum on July 24, 2019 for 4 million units in sales and streams.<ref name=\"riaa\"/> As of March 2020, the album has accrued 4.3 million units in the country in total,<ref name=units>{{cite news|url=http://roughstock.com/news/2020/03/44170-country-musics-most-consumed-albums-chart-march-9-2020|title=Country Music's Most-Consumed Albums Chart: March 9, 2020|work=Roughstock|first=Matt |last=Bjorke |date=March 9, 2020|accessdate= March 22, 2020}}</ref> with 2.6 million copies in traditional album sales.<ref name=\"sales\">{{cite web |url=http://roughstock.com/news/2020/03/44165-top-10-country-albums-pure-sales-chart-march-9-2020|title=Top 10 Country Albums Pure Sales Chart: March 9, 2020 |work=RoughStock|first=Matt |last=Bjorke |date= March 10, 2020 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|MC=85/100<ref name=metacritic />\n| rev1 = [[AbsolutePunk]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|9|10}}<ref name=\"absolutepunk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=3726595|title=\tChris Stapleton - Traveller - Album Review|accessdate=January 9, 2016|author=Manning, Craig|work=[[AbsolutePunk]]}}</ref>\n| rev2 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"allmusicreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/mw0002835889|title=Traveller - Chris Stapleton&nbsp;\u2014 Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards|accessdate=November 10, 2015|author=Erlewine, Stephen Thomas|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|publisher=[[All Media Network]]|work=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"bb\"/>\n| rev4 = Digital Journal\n| rev4Score = A<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Papadatos |first=Markos |date=November 8, 2015 |title=Review: Chris Stapleton spell-binding on 'Traveller' studio album |url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/a-and-e/music/review-chris-stapleton-spell-binding-on-traveller-studio-album/article/448803 |magazine=Digital Journal |access-date=December 21, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| rev5Score = 9/10<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/chris_stapleton-traveller |title=Chris Stapleton - Traveller |last=Henderson |first=Stuart |date=May 5, 2015 |work=Exclaim! |access-date=December 11, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev6 = [[NPR]]\n| rev6Score = (Favorable)<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2015/04/26/401769240/first-listen-chris-stapleton-traveller|title=Review: Chris Stapleton, 'Traveller'|accessdate=January 9, 2016|author=Powers, Ann|publisher=[[NPR]]|work=[[NPR]]}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/what-to-listen-to/best-country-music-albums-of-2015/|title=Best Country Music Albums of 2015|accessdate=January 14, 2016|author=Chilton, Martin|publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Wall Street Journal]]''\n| rev8Score = (Favorable)<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/traveller-by-chris-stapleton-review-1430777997|title='Traveller' by Chris Stapleton Review|accessdate=January 9, 2016|author=Fusilli Jim|publisher=[[Wall Street Journal]]|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref>\n}}\n''Traveller'' received critical acclaim upon its release. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from [[music critic]]s, the album has received an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 85, indicating \"universal acclaim\", based on 6 reviews.<ref name=metacritic>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/traveller/chris-stapleton|title=Critic Reviews for Traveller|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=January 5, 2016}}</ref> In a review for ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', editor Caitlin White gave the album four-out-of-five stars, describing ''Traveller'' as a \"solemn album, the work of a man gripped by life's impermanence\", noting \"undercurrents of regret, loss and resignation\" in songs like \"Daddy Doesn't Pray Anymore,\" \"Nobody to Blame\" and \"Devil Named Music\". About the record's sound direction, she commented \"Stapleton's songs are both rhythmic and nuanced, perhaps a by-product of years spent writing for others. They feature a cast of characters that remain likable even as they rush headlong into pursuit of ruin, fortune or chance.\" White concluded \"it's a triumphant debut, encapsulating the grit of life, turning it into a hell of a journey.\"<ref name=\"bb\">{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/6561354/chris-stapleton-traveller-solo-debut-album-review | title=Country Songwriter Chris Stapleton Copes With Loss on Triumphant Solo Debut: Album Review | publisher=Prometheus Global Media | work=Billboard | date=May 12, 2015 | accessdate=November 15, 2015 | author=White, Caitlin}}</ref> In ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', Randy Lewis wrote \"Stapleton's trenchant pen combines with his soul-drenched rasp of a voice for a moving exploration of the panoply of emotions in the human experience.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-ca-ms-best-pop-music-lewis-20151213-story.html |title=Best of 2015: 10 great albums in 2015 include works by Chris Stapleton, Rhiannon Giddens, Los Lobos and more |last=Lewis |first=Randy |date=December 11, 2015 |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=April 15, 2017}}</ref> \n\nCritics from ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' opined ''Traveller'' \"encapsulates everything that makes him one of the most powerful and unique voices in country music today: gravelly, soulful and full of songs that ring like instant classics without ever resting too deeply in the past.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/who-is-chris-stapleton-5-things-you-need-to-know-about-the-cma-king-20151105 |title=Who Is Chris Stapleton: 5 Things You Need to Know About the CMA King |date=November 5, 2015 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=April 15, 2017}}</ref> In their year-end summary they stated \"every track goes straight for the emotional jugular and give a glimpse inside a wildly introspective mind.\"<ref name=\"rollingst\">{{cite web | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/50-best-albums-of-2015-20151201/chris-stapleton-traveller-20151130 | title=The 50 Best Albums of 2015 | work=Rolling Stone | date=December 1, 2015 | accessdate=December 1, 2015}}</ref> Editor Owen R. Smith from ''[[The Seattle Times]]'' noted the instruments mandolin, banjo, pedal steel guitar \"are all given room to shine, even when Stapleton dips his toe into some menacing country rock in \u201cNobody to Blame\u201d or electrified bluesy swagger in \u201cMight As Well Get Stoned.\"\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/music/chris-stapleton-brings-back-introspective-old-school-country-music/ |title=Chris Stapleton brings back introspective, old-school country music |last=Smit |first=Owen R. |date=March 23, 2017 |work=The Seattle Times |access-date=April 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Publication\n! List\n! Rank\n! {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| ''[[American Songwriter]]''\n| Top 50 Albums of 2015\n|{{center|1}}\n|{{center|<ref>{{cite web | url=http://americansongwriter.com/2015/11/american-songwriters-top-50-albums-2015-presented-daddario/5/ | title=American Songwriter's Top 50 Albums of 2015: Presented by D'Addario | work=American Songwriter | date=November 23, 2015 | accessdate=December 20, 2017}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''\n| 25 Best Albums of 2015\n|{{center|13}}\n|{{center|<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/photos/6792633/best-albums-of-2015/13 | title=Billboard.com's 25 Best Albums of 2015: Critics' Picks | publisher=Prometheus Global Media | work=Billboard | date=December 15, 2015 | accessdate=December 15, 2015}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2| ''[[Brooklyn Magazine]]''\n| The Best of 2015\n|{{center|no order}}\n|{{center|<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=White |first=Caitlin |date=December 1, 2015 |title=The Best of 2015: A Look Back at the Best Albums of the Year |url=http://www.bkmag.com/2015/12/01/the-best-of-2015-a-look-back-at-the-best-albums-of-the-year/ |access-date=December 21, 2017}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| The 20 Best Country Albums of 2015\n|{{center|2}}\n|{{center|<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=White |first=Caitlin |date=December 2, 2015 |title=The 20 Best Country Albums Of 2015 |url=http://www.bkmag.com/2015/12/02/the-20-best-country-albums-of-2015/ |access-date=December 21, 2017}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| The 40 Best Albums of 2015\n|{{center|7}}\n|{{center|<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ew.com/gallery/best-albums-2015/2403163_7-chris-stapleton-traveller | title=The 40 Best Albums of 2015 | work=Entertainment Weekly | date=December 9, 2015 | accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| [[NPR]]\n| 50 Favorite Albums of 2015\n|{{center|no order}}\n|{{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2015/12/07/458447213/npr-musics-50-favorite-albums-of-2015|title=NPR Music's 50 Favorite Albums Of 2015 |work=NPR |date=December 7, 2015 |accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2| ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| 50 Best Albums of 2015\n|{{center|21}}\n|{{center|<ref name=\"rollingst\"/>}}\n|-\n| 40 Best Country Albums of 2015\n|{{center|3}}\n|{{center|<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/40-best-country-albums-of-2015-20151208/chris-stapleton-traveller-20151207 | title=40 Best Country Albums of 2015 | work=Rolling Stone | date=December 7, 2015 | accessdate=December 8, 2015}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| [[Stereogum]]\n| The 50 Best Albums of 2015\n|{{center|43}}\n|{{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stereogum.com/1845609/the-50-best-albums-of-2015/franchises/2015-in-review/|title=The 50 Best Albums Of 2015 |website=Stereogum |accessdate=December 10, 2015}}</ref>}}\n|}\n\n==Awards==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Award\n!Category\n!Result\n!{{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|2015\n|[[49th Annual Country Music Association Awards|Country Music Association Awards]]\n|[[Country Music Association Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]]\n|{{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref name=Tennessean-CMAs-2015>{{cite news|last1=Watts|first1=Cindy|title=CMA Awards: Stapleton, Little Big Town are winners|url=http://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2015/11/04/first-cma-award-little-big-town/75164062/|accessdate=5 November 2015|work=[[The Tennessean]]|date=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=7|2016\n|rowspan=2|[[58th Annual Grammy Awards|Grammy Awards]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]]\n|{{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/taylor-swift-kendrick-lamar-the-weeknd-lead-grammy-nominations-20151207 | title=Grammys: Taylor Swift, Kendrick Lamar, the Weeknd Lead Nominations | work=Rolling Stone | date=December 7, 2015 | accessdate=December 7, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Country Album|Best Country Album]]\n|rowspan=4 {{won}}\n|-\n|[[Academy of Country Music Awards]]\n|Album of the Year\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/country/7318846/acm-awards-2016-winners-list | title=ACM Awards 2016: See the Full List of Winners | work=Billboard | date=April 3, 2016 | accessdate=April 3, 2016 | author=Billboard Staff}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[2016 Billboard Music Awards|''Billboard'' Music Awards]]\n| [[Billboard Music Award for Top Country Album|Top Country Album]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|title=Billboard Music Awards 2016: Complete Winners List|author=Billboard Staff|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bbma/7378353/billboard-music-awards-2016-complete-winners-list|website=Billboard|date=May 22, 2016|accessdate=May 24, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[American Country Countdown Awards]]\n|Album of the Year\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/country/7350315/american-country-countdown-awards-2016-winners-list | title=American Country Count