ina/2013-06/12/content_16609614.htm Shenzhou flight history timeline]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100822194232/http://www.scaled.com/projects/tierone/combined_white_knight_spaceshipone_flight_tests SpaceShipOne flight history]\n*[http://russianspaceweb.com/soyuz-ms-10.html Soyuz MS-10 flight details]\n*[https://edition.cnn.com/2018/12/13/tech/virgin-galactic-reaches-50-mile-space/index.html VSS ''Unity'' flight details]\n*[https://www.iflscience.com/space/virgin-galactic-space-plane-just-took-its-first-test-passenger-to-space/]\n\n{{Space exploration lists and timelines}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List of human spaceflights, 2011-2020}}\n[[Category:Human spaceflight]]\n[[Category:Lists of astronauts|2010]]\n[[Category:Spaceflight timelines]]\n[[Category:21st century-related lists|Human spaceflights, 2011-present]]\n[[Category:2010s-related lists]]\n", "name_user": "Colinmartin74", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_human_spaceflights,_2011%E2%80%93present"}
{"title_page": "Luke the Evangelist", "text_new": "{{short description|One of the four traditionally ascribed authors of the canonical Gospels}}\n{{redirect|Saint Luke}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox saint\n|death_date     = March 84 AD\n|image          = Grandes Heures Anne de Bretagne Saint Luc.jpg\n|imagesize      =\n|caption        = Miniature of Saint Luke from the [[Grandes Heures of Anne of Brittany]] (1503\u20131508) by [[Jean&nbsp;Bourdichon]]\n|birth_place    = [[Antioch]], [[Syria (Roman province)|Syria]], [[Roman Empire]]\n|death_place    = [[Thebes, Greece|Thebes]], [[Boeotia]], Greece\n|feast_day      = 18 October\n|venerated_in   = all [[Christian Churches]] that venerate [[Saint]]s\n|titles         = Apostle, Evangelist\n|beatified_date =\n|beatified_place=\n|beatified_by   =\n|canonized_date =\n|attributes     = [[Four Evangelists|Evangelist]], Physician, a bishop, a book or a pen, a man accompanied by a winged [[ox]]/winged [[calf (animal)|calf]]/ox, a man painting an [[icon]] of the [[Blessed Virgin Mary]], a brush or a [[Palette (painting)|palette]] (referring to the tradition that he was a painter)\n|patronage=Artists, bachelors, physicians, surgeons, farmers, and others<ref>{{cite web|url=http://catholicsaints.info/saint-luke-the-evangelist/|title=Saint Luke the Evangelist|date=27 December 2008|publisher=}}</ref>\n|major_shrine   = [[Padua]], Italy\n|major_works    =\n|issues         =\n|prayer         =\n}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| embed            = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Luke of Antioch\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = \u03a4\u03b5\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03b5\u03c5\u03ac\u03b3\u03b3\u03b5\u03bb\u03bf \u0395140 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039c\u03b5\u03b3\u03af\u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039b\u03b1\u03cd\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2. \u0395\u03c5\u03b1\u03b3\u03b3\u03b5\u03bb\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2 \u039b\u03bf\u03c5\u03ba\u03ac\u03c2. 15\u03bf\u03c2 \u03b1\u03b9\u03ce\u03bd\u03b1\u03c2.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| genre             = [[Acts of the Apostles (genre)|Acts]]\n| caption          = \n| notableworks     = [[Gospel of Luke]] and [[Acts of the Apostles|Acts]]\n| occupation       = [[Christian missionary]], [[Artist]] and [[Historian]]\n| language         = [[Greek language|Greek]]}}\n'''Luke the Evangelist''' ([[Latin]]: ''[[Lucas (given name)|L\u016bc\u0101s]]'', {{lang-grc|\u039b\u03bf\u03c5\u03ba\u1fb6\u03c2}}, ''[[Loukas|Louk\u00e2s]]'', {{lang-he|\u05dc\u05d5\u05e7\u05d0\u05e1}}, ''L\u016bq\u0101s'', {{lang-arc|\u05dc\u05d5\u05e7\u05d0}}, ''L\u016bq\u0101&apos;'') is one of the [[Four Evangelists]]\u2014the four traditionally ascribed authors of the [[canonical Gospels]]. The Early [[Church Fathers]] ascribed to him authorship of both the [[Gospel of Luke]] and the [[Acts of the Apostles]], which would mean Luke contributed over a quarter of the text of the [[New Testament]], more than any other author. Prominent figures in early Christianity such as [[Jerome]] and [[Eusebius]] later reaffirmed his authorship, although a lack of conclusive evidence as to the identity of the author of the works has led to [[Authorship of Luke\u2013Acts|discussion]] in scholarly circles, both secular and religious.\n\nThe New Testament mentions Luke briefly a few times, and the [[Pauline epistles|Pauline]] [[Epistle to the Colossians]] refers to him as a physician (from Greek for 'one who heals'); thus he is thought to have been both a physician and a disciple of [[Paul the Apostle|Paul]]. Since the early years of the faith, Christians have regarded him as a [[saint]]. He is believed to have been a [[martyr]], reportedly having been hanged from an olive tree, though some believe otherwise.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/09420a.htm |title= Gospel of Saint Luke |last= Aherne|first= C.|date= 1910 |website= Catholic Encyclopedia |publisher= New Advent|access-date= 14 January 2019 |quote= it is controverted whether he actually died a martyr's death.}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Roman Catholic Church]] and other major denominations venerate him as '''Saint Luke the Evangelist''' and as a [[patron saint]] of artists, physicians, [[bachelors]], surgeons, students and butchers; his [[feast day]] is 18 October.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/saint/st-luke-the-evangelist-23|title=St. Luke The Evangelist|website=Catholic News Agency|access-date=16 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Life ==\nMany scholars believe that Luke was a [[Greeks|Greek]] physician who lived in the Greek city of [[Antioch, Turkey|Antioch]] in Ancient [[Syria (Roman province)|Syria]], although some other scholars and theologians think Luke was a [[Hellenistic Judaism|Hellenic Jew]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Understanding the Bible: A Reader's Introduction|last=Harris|first=Stephen L.|publisher=Mayfield|year=1985|isbn=0-87484-696-X|edition=2nd|location=Palo Alto|pages=266\u201368|chapter=The Gospels|author-link=Stephen L. Harris}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AeTdi13weAoC&pg=PA102|title=Luke the Priest: The Authority of the Author of the Third Gospel|last=Strelan|first=Rick|publisher=Ashgate Publishing|isbn=978-1-4094-7788-4|location=|date=May 2013|pages=102\u201310|chapter=Luke among the Scholars|via=Google Books}}</ref> Bart Koet, a researcher and professor of theology, has stated that it was widely accepted that the theology of [[Luke\u2013Acts]] points to a [[gentile]] Christian writing for a gentile audience, although he concludes that it is more plausible that Luke\u2013Acts is directed to a community made up of both Jewish and gentile Christians because there is stress on the scriptural roots of the gentile mission (see the use of Isaiah 49:6 in Luke\u2013Acts).<ref name=\" Bart J. Koet\">[[Bart J. Koet|Koet, Bart J.]], Five Studies on Interpretation of Scripture in Luke-Acts. Leuven University Press, 1989. pp. 157\u2013158</ref><ref name=\" Bart Koet\">[[Bart J. Koet|Koet, Bart J.]], Dreams and Scripture in Luke-Acts. Leuven University Press, 2006. pp. 4\u20135</ref> Gregory Sterling, Dean of the [[Yale Divinity School]], claims that he was either a [[Hellenistic Judaism|Hellenistic Jew]] or a [[god-fearer]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nHis earliest notice is in Paul's [[Epistle to Philemon]]\u2014{{Bibleref|Philemon|1:24}}. He is also mentioned in {{Bibleref|Colossians|4:14}} and {{bibleref|2 Timothy|4:11}}, two works commonly ascribed to Paul.<ref name=Milligan>''The New Testament Documents: Their Origin and Early History'', George Milligan, 1913, [[Macmillan and Co.]], p.&nbsp;149</ref><ref name=Mornin>''Saints: A Visual Guide'', Edward Mornin, Lorna Mornin, 2006, [[Eerdmans Books]], p.&nbsp;74</ref><ref name=aherne>\n[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/09420a.htm \"Gospel of Saint Luke\"], Aherne, Cornelius, [[The Catholic Encyclopedia]]. Vol. 9. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1910. 24 February 2013</ref><ref name=Smith>''New Outlook'', Alfred Emanuel Smith, 1935, Outlook Pub. Co., p.&nbsp;792</ref><ref name=Harnack>''New Testament Studies. I. Luke the Physician: The Author of the Third Gospel'', Adolf von Harnack, 1907, Williams & Norgate; [[G.P. Putnam's Sons]], p.&nbsp;5</ref> The next earliest account of Luke is in the ''Anti-[[Marcionite]] Prologue to the Gospel of Luke'', a document once thought to date to the 2nd century, but which has more recently been dated to the later 4th century.{{Citation needed|date=September 2015}} [[Helmut Koester]], however, claims that the following part, the only part preserved in the original [[Greek language|Greek]], may have been composed in the late 2nd century:\n\n{{quote|Luke, was born in [[Antioch]], by profession, was a physician.<ref name=Hackett>''A Commentary on the Original Text of the Acts of the Apostles'', [[Horatio Balch Hackett]], 1858, Gould and Lincoln; Sheldon, Blakeman & Co., p.&nbsp;12</ref> He had become a disciple of the apostle Paul and later followed Paul until his [Paul's] martyrdom. He died at the age of 84 years. (p.&nbsp;335)}}\n\n[[File:Brooklyn Museum - Saint Luke (Saint Luc) - James Tissot.jpg|thumb|upright|[[James Tissot]], ''Saint Luke (Saint Luc)'', [[Brooklyn Museum]]]]\n\n[[Epiphanius of Salamis|Epiphanius]] states that Luke was one of the [[Seventy Apostles]] (''[[Panarion]]'' 51.11), and [[John Chrysostom]] indicates at one point that the \"brother\" Paul mentions in the Second Epistle to the Corinthians 8:18 is either Luke or [[Barnabas]]. (''Homily 18 on Second Corinthians'' on 2 Corinthians 8:18)\n\nIf one accepts that Luke was indeed the author of the Gospel bearing his name and also the ''Acts of the Apostles'', certain details of his personal life can be reasonably assumed. While he does exclude himself from those who were eyewitnesses to Jesus' ministry, he repeatedly uses the word \"we\" in describing the Pauline missions in ''Acts of the Apostles'', indicating that he was personally there at those times.<ref name=EB>''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'', Microp\u00e6dia vol. 7, pp.&nbsp;554\u201355. Chicago: [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]], Inc, 1998. {{ISBN|0-85229-633-9}}.</ref>\n\nThere is similar evidence that Luke resided in [[Troad|Troas]], the province which included the ruins of ancient [[Troy]], in that he writes in ''Acts'' in the third person about Paul and his travels until they get to Troas, where he switches to the first person plural. The \"we\" section of ''Acts'' continues until the group leaves [[Philippi]], when his writing goes back to the third person. This change happens again when the group returns to Philippi. There are three \"we sections\" in ''Acts'', all following this rule. Luke never stated, however, that he lived in Troas, and this is the only evidence that he did.{{Citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n\n[[File:Bodleian Library MS. Arm. d.13. Armenian Gospels-0043-0.jpg|thumb|upright|Luke as depicted in the head-piece of an Armenian Gospel manuscript from 1609, held at the [[Bodleian Library]]]]\n\nThe composition of the writings, as well as the range of vocabulary used, indicate that the author was an educated man. A quote in the [[Epistle to the Colossians]] differentiates between Luke and other colleagues \"of the [[Circumcision controversy in early Christianity|circumcision]].\"\n\n{{quote|10 My fellow prisoner Aristarchus sends you his greetings, as does Mark, the cousin of Barnabas. 11 Jesus, who is called Justus, also sends greetings. These are the only Jews among my co-workers for the kingdom of God, and they have proved a comfort to me. ... 14 Our dear friend Luke, the doctor, and Demas send greetings. {{Bibleref|Colossians|4:10\u201311, 14}}.}}\n\nThis comment has traditionally caused commentators to conclude that Luke was a gentile. If this were true, it would make Luke the only writer of the New Testament who can clearly be identified as not being Jewish. However, that is not the only possibility. Although Luke is considered likely to have been a gentile Christian, some scholars believe him to have been a [[Hellenistic Jew|Hellenized Jew]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>Thomas S. McCall, Th.D. [http://www.levitt.com/essays/luke Was Luke a Gentile?]</ref> The phrase could just as easily be used to differentiate between those [[Jewish Christians|Christians who strictly observed the rituals of Judaism]] and those who did not.<ref name=EB/>\n\nLuke's presence in [[Rome]] with the Apostle Paul near the end of Paul's life was attested by 2 Timothy 4:11: \"Only Luke is with me\". In the last chapter of the Book of Acts, widely attributed to Luke, there are several accounts in the first person also affirming Luke's presence in Rome, including {{Bibleref|Acts|28:16}}: \"And when we came to Rome...\" According to some accounts,{{Which|date=September 2014}} Luke also contributed to the [[authorship of the Epistle to the Hebrews]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/07181a.htm|title=Catholic Encyclopedia: Epistle to the Hebrews|website=www.newadvent.org|access-date=10 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nLuke died at age 84 in [[Boeotia]], according to a \"fairly early and widespread tradition\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Butler's Lives of the Saints|last=|first=|publisher=HarperColllins Publishers|isbn=978-0-06-069299-5|editor-last=Walsh|editor-first=Michael|location=New York|date=5 July 1991|pages=[https://archive.org/details/butlerslivesofsa00butl/page/342 342]|url=https://archive.org/details/butlerslivesofsa00butl/page/342}}</ref> According to [[Nikephoros Kallistos Xanthopoulos]], Greek historian of the 14th century (and others), Luke's tomb was located in [[Thebes (Greece)|Thebes]], whence his relics were transferred to [[Constantinople]] in the year 357.<ref>'Ecclesiasticae Historiae Nicephori Callisti', Lib. II, Cap. XLIII, in J.P. Migne (ed.), ''Patrologia Graeca'' Vol. 145 (Paris 1901), [https://archive.org/stream/patrologicursus11migngoog#page/n441/mode/2up pp./cols. 875-878] (Internet Archive). (In Greek and Latin parallel).</ref>\n\n== Authorship of Luke and Acts ==\n{{see also|Authorship of Luke\u2013Acts}}\nThe Gospel of Luke does not name its author.<ref name=sanders>E. P. Sanders, ''The Historical Figure of Jesus'', (Penguin, 1995) pp. 63\u201364.</ref><ref name=ehrman>Bart D. Ehrman (2000:43) ''The New Testament: a historical introduction to early Christian writings.'' Oxford University Press.</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VrmW1eXBILgC&pg=PA328 |page=328 |title=Invitation to the Gospels |isbn=9780809140725 |last1=Senior |first1=Donald |last2=Achtemeier |first2=Paul J. |last3=Karris |first3=Robert J. |year=2002 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5SSytjasmAgC&pg=PA43 |page=43 |title=The Synoptic Gospels: An Introduction |isbn=9780664223496 |last1=Nickle |first1=Keith Fullerton |date=January 2001 }}</ref> The Gospel was not nor does it claim to be written by direct witnesses to the reported events, unlike Acts beginning in the sixteenth chapter.<ref name=lost>{{cite book |authorlink=Bart D. Ehrman |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=URdACxKubDIC&pg=PA235 |page=235 |title = Lost Christianities: The Battles for Scripture and the Faiths We Never Knew|isbn = 9780195182491|last1 = Ehrman|first1 = Bart D.|year = 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |authorlink=Bart D. Ehrman |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vbLK6kn5T-EC&pg=PA110 |page=110 |title = Truth and Fiction in the da Vinci Code: A Historian Reveals What We Really Know about Jesus, Mary Magdalene, and Constantine|isbn = 9780195346169|last1 = Ehrman|first1 = Bart D.|date = November 2004}}</ref><ref name=iuda>{{cite book |authorlink=Bart D. Ehrman |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oBuJMhJlTYwC&pg=PA143 |page=143 |title = The Lost Gospel of Judas Iscariot: A New Look at Betrayer and Betrayed|isbn = 9780199711048|last1 = Ehrman|first1 = Bart D.|date = 9 October 2006}}</ref> \n\nThe earliest manuscript of the Gospel (Papyrus 75 = Papyrus Bodmer XIV-XV), dated circa AD&nbsp;200, ascribes the work to Luke; as did [[Irenaeus]], writing circa AD&nbsp;180, and the [[Muratorian fragment]] from AD&nbsp;170.<ref>[[Raymond E. Brown|Brown, Raymond E.]] ''An Introduction to the New Testament'', p. 267. [[Anchor Bible]]; 1st edition (13 October 1997). {{ISBN|978-0-385-24767-2}}.</ref>\n\nThe gospel of Luke and the [[Acts of the Apostles]] make up a two-volume work which scholars call [[Luke\u2013Acts]]. Together they account for 27.5% of the [[New Testament]], the largest contribution by a single author.{{sfn|Boring|2012|p=556}}\n\n[[File:De heilige Lucas schildert de Madonna - Maarten van Heemskerck-1532.JPG|thumb|''Luke paints the Madonna and the Baby Jesus'', by [[Maarten van Heemskerck]], 1532]]\n\n== As a historian ==\n{{See also|Historical reliability of the Acts of the Apostles|Census of Quirinius|Chronology of Jesus}}\n[[File:Luke by roslin.jpg|thumb|upright|A medieval Armenian illumination of Luke, by [[Toros Roslin]]]]\nMost scholars understand Luke's works ([[Luke\u2013Acts]]) in the tradition of [[Greek historiography]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|chapter-url=http://religion-online.org/showchapter.asp?title=1116&C=1230|title=A Historical Introduction to the New Testament|last=Grant|first=Robert M.|publisher=Harper & Row|year=1963|chapter=Chapter 10: The Gospel of Luke and the Book of Acts|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100621102923/http://religion-online.org/showchapter.asp?title=1116&C=1230|archive-date=21 June 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> The preface of ''The Gospel of Luke''<ref name=preface>{{cite web | url = http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Luke%20(1:1-4)&version=NLT | title = Luke 1:1\u20134}}</ref> drawing on historical investigation identified the work to the readers as belonging to the genre of history.<ref>Richard Bauckham, ''Jesus and the Eyewitnesses''. 117.</ref> There is disagreement about how best to treat Luke's writings, with some historians{{who|date=February 2019}} regarding Luke as highly accurate, and others{{who|date=February 2019}} taking a more critical approach.\n\nBased on his accurate description of towns, cities and islands, as well as correctly naming various official titles, archaeologist [[William Mitchell Ramsay|Sir William Ramsay]] wrote that \"Luke is a historian of the first rank; not merely are his statements of fact trustworthy... [he] should be placed along with the very greatest of historians.\"<ref>Ramsay, ''The Bearing of Recent Discovery on the Trustworthiness of the New Testament'', 222, 1915</ref> Professor of Classics at [[Auckland University]], [[E.M. Blaiklock]], wrote: \"For accuracy of detail, and for evocation of atmosphere, Luke stands, in fact, with [[Thucydides]]. The Acts of the Apostles is not shoddy product of pious imagining, but a trustworthy record... it was the spadework of archaeology which first revealed the truth.\"<ref>Blaiklock, The Archaeology of the New Testament, p. 96, Zondervan Publishing Houst, Grand Rapids, Michigan, 1970.</ref> New Testament scholar Colin Hemer has made a number of advancements in understanding the historical nature and accuracy of Luke's writings.<ref>Hemer, \"The Book of Acts in the Setting of Hellenic History\", 104\u201307, as summarized by MacDowell.</ref>\n\nOn the purpose of Acts, New Testament Scholar [[Luke Timothy Johnson]] has noted that \"Luke's account is selected and shaped to suit his apologetic interests, not in defiance of but in conformity to ancient standards of historiography.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Johnson|first=Luke Timothy|authorlink=Luke Timothy Johnson|title=The Acts of the Apostles|publisher=The Liturgical Press|year=1992|pages=474\u201376|url= http://www.earlychristianwritings.com/luke.html}}</ref> Such a position is shared by most commentators such as Richard Heard who sees historical deficiencies as arising from \"special objects in writing and to the limitations of his sources of information.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Heard|first=Richard|title=An Introduction to the New Testament|chapter=13: The Acts of the Apostles|publisher=Harper & Brothers|year=1950|chapter-url=http://www.religion-online.org/showbook.asp?title=531|access-date=23 November 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620161529/http://religion-online.org/showbook.asp?title=531|archive-date=20 June 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nDuring modern times, Luke's competence as a historian is questioned, depending upon one's ''a priori'' view of the supernatural.<ref name=\"markpowell\"/> Since post-[[Age of Enlightenment|Enlightenment]] historians work with [[methodological naturalism]],<ref>McGrew, Timothy, \"Miracles\", The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy (Winter 2015 Edition), Edward N. Zalta (ed.), http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/miracles/<br>Flew, Antony, 1966, ''God and Philosophy'', London: Hutchinson.<br>Ehrman, Bart D., 2003, ''The New Testament: A Historical Introduction to the Early Christian Writings'', 3rd ed., New York: Oxford University Press.<br>Bradley, Francis Herbert, 1874, \"The Presuppositions of Critical History,\" in ''Collected Essays'', vol. 1, Oxford, Clarendon Press, 1935.<br>McGrew's conclusion: historians work with [[methodological naturalism]], which precludes them from establishing miracles as objective historical facts (Flew 1966: 146; cf. Bradley 1874/1935; Ehrman 2003: 229).</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bringyou.to/apologetics/p96.htm|title=William Lane Craig and Bart Ehrman \"Is There Historical Evidence for the Resurrection of Jesus?\"|first1=Bart|last1=Ehrman|authorlink1=Bart D. Ehrman|first2=William Lane|last2=Craig|authorlink2=William Lane Craig|date=28 March 2006|publisher=bringyou.to|location=College of the Holy Cross, Worcester, Massachusetts|accessdate=11 August 2010|quote=Historians can only establish what probably happened in the past, and by definition a miracle is the least probable occurrence. And so, by the very nature of the canons of historical research, we can't claim historically that a miracle probably happened. By definition, it probably didn't. And history can only establish what probably did.}}</ref> such historians would see a narrative that relates supernatural, fantastic things like angels, demons etc., as problematic as a historical source. Mark Powell claims that \"it is doubtful whether the writing of history was ever Luke's intent. Luke wrote to proclaim, to persuade, and to interpret; he did not write to preserve records for posterity. An awareness of this, has been, for many, the final nail in Luke the historian's coffin.\"<ref name=\"markpowell\">{{cite book|last=Powell|first=Mark|title=What are they saying about Luke?|year=1989|publisher=Paulist Press|isbn=0-8091-3111-0|page=6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9jRu8_-GlKMC&pg=PA6 }}</ref>\n\nRobert M. Grant has noted that although Luke saw himself within the historical tradition, his work contains a number of statistical improbabilities, such as the sizable crowd addressed by Peter in Acts 4:4. He has also noted chronological difficulties whereby Luke \"has [[Gamaliel]] refer to [[Theudas]] and [[Judas of Galilee|Judas]] in the wrong order, and Theudas actually rebelled about a decade after Gamaliel spoke (5:36\u20137)\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== As an artist ==\n[[File:Evangelist Luka pishustchiy ikonu.jpg|thumb|upright|Luke the Evangelist painting the first [[icon]] of the Virgin Mary]]\nChristian tradition, starting from the 8th century, states that Luke was the first [[icon]] painter. He is said to have painted pictures of the [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Virgin Mary]] and Child, in particular the [[Hodegetria]] image in [[Constantinople]] (now lost). Starting from the 11th century, a number of painted images were venerated as his autograph works, including the [[Black Madonna of Cz\u0119stochowa]] and [[Theotokos of Vladimir|Our Lady of Vladimir]]. He was also said to have painted Saints [[Saint Peter|Peter]] and Paul, and to have illustrated a gospel book with a full cycle of miniatures.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grigg|first=Robert|date=1987|title=Byzantine Credulity as an Impediment to Antiquarianism|url=|journal=[[Gesta (journal)|Gesta]]|volume=26|issue=1|pages=3\u20139|doi=10.2307/767073|jstor=767073}}</ref><ref>The basic study on the legends concerning Saint Luke as a painter is Michele Bacci, Il pennello dell'Evangelista. Storia delle immagini sacre attribuite a san Luca (Pisa: Gisem, 1998).</ref>\n\nLate medieval [[Guild of Saint Luke|Guilds of Saint Luke]] in the cities of Late Medieval Europe, especially [[Flanders]], or the \"[[Accademia di San Luca]]\" (Academy of Saint Luke) in Rome\u2014imitated in many other European cities during the 16th century\u2014gathered together and protected painters. The tradition that Luke painted icons of Mary and Jesus has been common, particularly in [[Eastern Orthodoxy]]. The tradition also has support from the [[Saint Thomas Christians]] of India who claim to still have one of the [[Theotokos]] icons that Saint Luke painted and which St. Thomas brought to India.<ref>Father '''H. Hosten''' in his book ''Antiquities'' notes the following \"The picture at the mount is one of the oldest, and, therefore, one of the most venerable Christian paintings to be had in India. Other traditions hold that St. Luke painted two icons which currently are in Greece: the \"Theotokos Mega Spileotissa\" (Our Lady of the Great Cave, where supposedly Saint Luke lived for a period of time in asceticism) and the \"Panagia Soumela\", and \"Panagia Kykkou\" which are in Cyprus.\"</ref>\n\n== Symbol ==\n[[File:Hermen Rode 001.jpg|thumb|upright|Luke and the [[The Madonna|Madonna]], Altar of the Guild of Saint Luke, [[Hermen Rode]], [[L\u00fcbeck]] (1484)]]\nIn traditional depictions, such as paintings, [[evangelist portrait]]s, and church [[mosaic]]s, Saint Luke is often accompanied by an [[ox]] or [[bull]], usually having wings. Sometimes only the symbol is shown, especially when in a combination of those of all [[Four Evangelists]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Gospel Figures in Art|last=Zuffi|first=Stefano|publisher=Getty Publications|year=2003|isbn=0-89236-727-X|location=|pages=|chapter=The Evangelists and their symbols}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author1=George Ashdown Audsley |author2= William Audsley |title=Handbook of Christian Symbolism |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/handbookofchrist00auds |chapter=Chapter VI. Symbols and emblems of the Evangelists and the Apostles |year=1865}} Reprinted by Kessinger Publishing, 2003, {{ISBN|978-0-7661-5437-7}}.</ref>\n\n== Relics ==\nDespot [[\u0110ura\u0111 Brankovi\u0107|George of Serbia]] purportedly bought the relics from the Ottoman sultan [[Murad II]] for 30,000 gold coins. After the [[Ottoman conquest of Bosnia]], the kingdom's last queen, George's granddaughter [[Mary of Serbia, Queen of Bosnia|Mary]], who had brought the relics with her from Serbia as her dowry, sold them to the [[Venetian Republic]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Bosnian Church: A New Interpretation: A Study of the Bosnian Church and Its Place in State and Society from the 13th to the 15th Centuries|last=Van Antwerp Fine|first=John|publisher=East European Quarterly|year=1975|isbn=|location=|pages=331}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, the then [[Greek Orthodox]] Metropolitan [[Archbishop Ieronymos II of Athens|Ieronymos]] of [[Thebes, Greece|Thebes and Levathia]] (the current Archbishop of [[Athens]] and All Greece) requested from [[Diocese of Padua|Bishop Antonio Mattiazzo of Padua]] the return of \"a significant fragment of the relics of St. Luke to be placed on the site where the holy tomb of the Evangelist is located and venerated today\". This prompted a scientific investigation of the relics in [[Padua]], and by numerous lines of empirical evidence (archeological analyses of the Tomb in [[Thebes, Greece|Thebes]] and the Reliquary of [[Padua]], anatomical analyses of the remains, [[carbon-14 dating]], comparison with the purported skull of the Evangelist located in [[Prague]]) confirmed that these were the remains of an individual of Syrian descent who died between 416 BC and AD 72.<ref>V.T.W. Marin and F.G.B Trolese (eds.), ''San Luca evangelista testimone della fede che unisce. Atti del Congresso internazionale, Padova, 16-21 ottobre 2000 Volumes I-III'' (Padua: Istituto per la storia ecclesiastica Padovana, 2003). This is a three-volume work documenting the international congress in Padua in 2000 on the topic of Luke the evangelist, including his relics.</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/italy/1360095/DNA-test-pinpoints-St-Luke-the-apostles-remains-to-Padua.html|title=DNA test pinpoints St Luke the apostle's remains to Padua|last=Craig|first=Olga|date=21 October 2001|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=}}</ref> The [[Diocese of Padua|Bishop of Padua]] then delivered to Metropolitan Ieronymos the rib of Saint Luke that was closest to his heart to be kept at his tomb in Thebes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.traces-cl.com/archive/2000/novembre/luca.htm|title=The Beloved Physician|last=Tornielli|first=Andrea|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090607075349/http://www.traces-cl.com/archive/2000/novembre/luca.htm|archive-date=7 June 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/10/16/world/body-of-st-luke-gains-credibility.html|title=Body of St. Luke Gains Credibility|last=Wade|first=Nicholas|date=16 October 2001|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThus, the relics of Saint Luke are divided as follows:\n* The body, in the [[Abbey of Santa Giustina]] in Padua;\n* The head, in the [[St. Vitus Cathedral]] in Prague;\n* A rib, at his tomb in Thebes.\n\n==Gallery ==\n<gallery widths=\"154px\" heights=\"200px\" perrow=\"4\" caption=\"Luke the Evangelist\">\n\nFile:Luke_writing.jpg\nFile:142082810-612x612.jpg\nFile:Luke_the_Evangelist.jpg\nFile:Saint_luke.jpg\nFile:Nuremberg_chronicles_f_108r_1.png\nFile:Icon of the blessed Virgin Mary by Luke the Evangelist.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Wikipedia books|Gospel}}\n* [[John the Evangelist]]\n* [[Mark the Evangelist]]\n* [[Matthew the Apostle|Matthew the Evangelist]]\n\n== References and sources ==\n'''References'''\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n* Michele Bacci, ''Il pennello dell'Evangelista. Storia delle immagini sacre attribuite a san Luca'', Pisa: Gisem-Ets, 1998.\n* [[I. Howard Marshall]]. ''Luke: Historian and Theologian''. Downers Grove, Illinois: InterVarsity Press.\n* {{Cite book\n|last = Boring\n|first = M. Eugene\n|title = An Introduction to the New Testament: History, Literature, Theology\n|publisher = Westminster John Knox Press\n|year = 2012\n|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=leFrgkyEtusC&pg=PA556\n|ref = harv\n|isbn = 9780664255923\n}}\n* [[F. F. Bruce]], ''The Speeches in the Acts of the Apostles.'' London: The Tyndale Press, 1942.[http://www.biblicalstudies.org.uk/pdf/speeches_bruce.pdf ]\n* Helmut Koester. ''Ancient Christian Gospels''. Harrisburg, Pennsylvania: Trinity Press International, 1999.\n* Burton L. Mack. ''Who Wrote the New Testament?: The Making of the Christian Myth''. San Francisco, California: HarperCollins, 1996.\n* J. Wenham, \"The Identification of Luke\", ''[[Evangelical Quarterly]]'' 63 (1991), 3\u201344\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Luke the Evangelist}}\n{{AmCyc Poster|Luke, Saint|Luke the Evangelist}}\n* [http://www.allaboutthejourney.org/saint-luke.htm Biblical Interpretation of Texts of Saint Luke]\n* [http://www.earlychristianwritings.com/luke.html Early Christian Writings: ''Gospel of Luke'' e-texts, introductions]\n* [http://www.pnas.org/cgi/content/full/211540498v1?maxtoshow National Academy of Sciences on Luke the Evangelist]\n* [http://www.catholic.org/saints/saint.php?saint_id=76 Patron Saint Luke]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070311192236/http://www.glaubenswege.ch/Evangelist_Lukas.html Photo of the grave of Luke in Padua (in German)]\n* [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A05E6D61E3FF935A25753C1A9679C8B63 DNA testing of the Saint Luke corpse]\n* [http://www.santiebeati.it/dettaglio/21800, Santiebeati]\n* [http://www.catholic.org/saints/saint.php?saint_id=76, Catholic Online]\n\n{{New Testament people}}\n{{Gospel of Luke}}\n{{Acts of the Apostles}}\n{{Catholic saints}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Luke The Evangelist}}\n[[Category:84 deaths]]\n[[Category:1st-century Christian martyrs]]\n[[Category:1st-century Greek people]]\n[[Category:1st-century physicians]]\n[[Category:1st-century writers]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek physicians]]\n[[Category:Ancient Syrian physicians]]\n[[Category:Antiochian Greek Christians]]\n[[Category:Black Madonna of Cz\u0119stochowa]]\n[[Category:Christianity in Roman Achaea]]\n[[Category:Gospel of Luke]]\n[[Category:Saints from Roman Anatolia]]\n[[Category:People in Acts of the Apostles]]\n[[Category:People in the Pauline epistles]]\n[[Category:Seventy disciples]]\n[[Category:Saints from Roman Syria]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Four Evangelists]]\n[[Category:Burials at the Church of the Holy Apostles]]\n[[Category:Burials in Greece]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|One of the four traditionally ascribed authors of the canonical Gospels}}\n{{redirect|Saint Luke}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox saint\n|death_date     = March 84 AD\n|image          = Grandes Heures Anne de Bretagne Saint Luc.jpg\n|imagesize      =\n|caption        = Miniature of Saint Luke from the [[Grandes Heures of Anne of Brittany]] (1503\u20131508) by [[Jean&nbsp;Bourdichon]]\n|birth_place    = [[Antioch]], [[Syria (Roman province)|Syria]], [[Roman Empire]]\n|death_place    = [[Thebes, Greece|Thebes]], [[Boeotia]], Greece\n|feast_day      = 18 October\n|venerated_in   = all [[Christian Churches]] that venerate [[Saint]]s\n|titles         = Apostle, Evangelist\n|beatified_date =\n|beatified_place=\n|beatified_by   =\n|canonized_date =\n|attributes     = [[Four Evangelists|Evangelist]], Physician, a bishop, a book or a pen, a man accompanied by a winged [[ox]]/winged [[calf (animal)|calf]]/ox, a man painting an [[icon]] of the [[Blessed Virgin Mary]], a brush or a [[Palette (painting)|palette]] (referring to the tradition that he was a painter)\n|patronage=Artists, bachelors, physicians, surgeons, farmers, and others<ref>{{cite web|url=http://catholicsaints.info/saint-luke-the-evangelist/|title=Saint Luke the Evangelist|date=27 December 2008|publisher=}}</ref>\n|major_shrine   = [[Padua]], Italy\n|major_works    =\n|issues         =\n|prayer         =\n}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| embed            = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Luke of Antioch\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = \u03a4\u03b5\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03b5\u03c5\u03ac\u03b3\u03b3\u03b5\u03bb\u03bf \u0395140 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039c\u03b5\u03b3\u03af\u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039b\u03b1\u03cd\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2. \u0395\u03c5\u03b1\u03b3\u03b3\u03b5\u03bb\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2 \u039b\u03bf\u03c5\u03ba\u03ac\u03c2. 15\u03bf\u03c2 \u03b1\u03b9\u03ce\u03bd\u03b1\u03c2.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| genre             = [[Acts of the Apostles (genre)|Acts]]\n| caption          = \n| notableworks     = [[Gospel of Luke]] and [[Acts of the Apostles|Acts]]\n| occupation       = [[Christian missionary]], [[Artist]] and [[Historian]]\n| language         = [[Greek language|Greek]]}}\n'''Luke the Evangelist''' ([[Latin]]: ''[[Lucas (given name)|L\u016bc\u0101s]]'', {{lang-grc|\u039b\u03bf\u03c5\u03ba\u1fb6\u03c2}}, ''[[Loukas|Louk\u00e2s]]'', {{lang-he|\u05dc\u05d5\u05e7\u05d0\u05e1}}, ''L\u016bq\u0101s'', {{lang-arc|\u05dc\u05d5\u05e7\u05d0}}, ''L\u016bq\u0101&apos;'') is one of the [[Four Evangelists]]\u2014the four traditionally ascribed authors of the [[canonical Gospels]]. The Early [[Church Fathers]] ascribed to him authorship of both the [[Gospel of Luke]] and the [[Acts of the Apostles]], which would mean Luke contributed over a quarter of the text of the [[New Testament]], more than any other author. Prominent figures in early Christianity such as [[Jerome]] and [[Eusebius]] later reaffirmed his authorship, although a lack of conclusive evidence as to the identity of the author of the works has led to [[Authorship of Luke\u2013Acts|discussion]] in scholarly circles, both secular and religious.\n\nThe New Testament mentions Luke briefly a few times, and the [[Pauline epistles|Pauline]] [[Epistle to the Colossians]] refers to him as a physician (from Greek for 'one who heals'); thus he is thought to have been both a physician and a disciple of [[Paul the Apostle|Paul]]. Since the early years of the faith, Christians have regarded him as a [[saint]]. He is believed to have been a [[martyr]], reportedly having been hanged from an olive tree, though some believe otherwise.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/09420a.htm |title= Gospel of Saint Luke |last= Aherne|first= C.|date= 1910 |website= Catholic Encyclopedia |publisher= New Advent|access-date= 14 January 2019 |quote= it is controverted whether he actually died a martyr's death.}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Roman Catholic Church]] and other major denominations venerate him as '''Saint Luke the Evangelist''' and as a [[patron saint]] of artists, physicians, [[bachelors]], surgeons, students and butchers; his [[feast day]] is 18 October.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/saint/st-luke-the-evangelist-23|title=St. Luke The Evangelist|website=Catholic News Agency|access-date=2018-10-16|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Life ==\nMany scholars believe that Luke was a [[Greeks|Greek]] physician who lived in the Greek city of [[Antioch, Turkey|Antioch]] in Ancient [[Syria (Roman province)|Syria]], although some other scholars and theologians think Luke was a [[Hellenistic Judaism|Hellenic Jew]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Understanding the Bible: A Reader's Introduction|last=Harris|first=Stephen L.|publisher=Mayfield|year=1985|isbn=0-87484-696-X|edition=2nd|location=Palo Alto|pages=266\u201368|chapter=The Gospels|author-link=Stephen L. Harris}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AeTdi13weAoC&pg=PA102|title=Luke the Priest: The Authority of the Author of the Third Gospel|last=Strelan|first=Rick|publisher=Ashgate Publishing|isbn=978-1-4094-7788-4|location=|date=May 2013|pages=102\u201310|chapter=Luke among the Scholars|via=Google Books}}</ref> Bart Koet, a researcher and professor of theology, has stated that it was widely accepted that the theology of [[Luke\u2013Acts]] points to a [[gentile]] Christian writing for a gentile audience, although he concludes that it is more plausible that Luke\u2013Acts is directed to a community made up of both Jewish and gentile Christians because there is stress on the scriptural roots of the gentile mission (see the use of Isaiah 49:6 in Luke\u2013Acts).<ref name=\" Bart J. Koet\">[[Bart J. Koet|Koet, Bart J.]], Five Studies on Interpretation of Scripture in Luke-Acts. Leuven University Press, 1989. pp. 157\u2013158</ref><ref name=\" Bart Koet\">[[Bart J. Koet|Koet, Bart J.]], Dreams and Scripture in Luke-Acts. Leuven University Press, 2006. pp. 4\u20135</ref> Gregory Sterling, Dean of the [[Yale Divinity School]], claims that he was either a [[Hellenistic Judaism|Hellenistic Jew]] or a [[god-fearer]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nHis earliest notice is in Paul's [[Epistle to Philemon]]\u2014{{Bibleref|Philemon|1:24}}. He is also mentioned in {{Bibleref|Colossians|4:14}} and {{bibleref|2 Timothy|4:11}}, two works commonly ascribed to Paul.<ref name=Milligan>''The New Testament Documents: Their Origin and Early History'', George Milligan, 1913, [[Macmillan and Co.]], p.&nbsp;149</ref><ref name=Mornin>''Saints: A Visual Guide'', Edward Mornin, Lorna Mornin, 2006, [[Eerdmans Books]], p.&nbsp;74</ref><ref name=aherne>\n[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/09420a.htm \"Gospel of Saint Luke\"], Aherne, Cornelius, [[The Catholic Encyclopedia]]. Vol. 9. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1910. 24 February 2013</ref><ref name=Smith>''New Outlook'', Alfred Emanuel Smith, 1935, Outlook Pub. Co., p.&nbsp;792</ref><ref name=Harnack>''New Testament Studies. I. Luke the Physician: The Author of the Third Gospel'', Adolf von Harnack, 1907, Williams & Norgate; [[G.P. Putnam's Sons]], p.&nbsp;5</ref> The next earliest account of Luke is in the ''Anti-[[Marcionite]] Prologue to the Gospel of Luke'', a document once thought to date to the 2nd century, but which has more recently been dated to the later 4th century.{{Citation needed|date=September 2015}} [[Helmut Koester]], however, claims that the following part, the only part preserved in the original [[Greek language|Greek]], may have been composed in the late 2nd century:\n\n{{quote|Luke, was born in [[Antioch]], by profession, was a physician.<ref name=Hackett>''A Commentary on the Original Text of the Acts of the Apostles'', [[Horatio Balch Hackett]], 1858, Gould and Lincoln; Sheldon, Blakeman & Co., p.&nbsp;12</ref> He had become a disciple of the apostle Paul and later followed Paul until his [Paul's] martyrdom. He died at the age of 84 years. (p.&nbsp;335)}}\n\n[[File:Brooklyn Museum - Saint Luke (Saint Luc) - James Tissot.jpg|thumb|upright|[[James Tissot]], ''Saint Luke (Saint Luc)'', [[Brooklyn Museum]]]]\n\n[[Epiphanius of Salamis|Epiphanius]] states that Luke was one of the [[Seventy Apostles]] (''[[Panarion]]'' 51.11), and [[John Chrysostom]] indicates at one point that the \"brother\" Paul mentions in the Second Epistle to the Corinthians 8:18 is either Luke or [[Barnabas]]. (''Homily 18 on Second Corinthians'' on 2 Corinthians 8:18)\n\nIf one accepts that Luke was indeed the author of the Gospel bearing his name and also the ''Acts of the Apostles'', certain details of his personal life can be reasonably assumed. While he does exclude himself from those who were eyewitnesses to Jesus' ministry, he repeatedly uses the word \"we\" in describing the Pauline missions in ''Acts of the Apostles'', indicating that he was personally there at those times.<ref name=EB>''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'', Microp\u00e6dia vol. 7, pp.&nbsp;554\u201355. Chicago: [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]], Inc, 1998. {{ISBN|0-85229-633-9}}.</ref>\n\nThere is similar evidence that Luke resided in [[Troad|Troas]], the province which included the ruins of ancient [[Troy]], in that he writes in ''Acts'' in the third person about Paul and his travels until they get to Troas, where he switches to the first person plural. The \"we\" section of ''Acts'' continues until the group leaves [[Philippi]], when his writing goes back to the third person. This change happens again when the group returns to Philippi. There are three \"we sections\" in ''Acts'', all following this rule. Luke never stated, however, that he lived in Troas, and this is the only evidence that he did.{{Citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n\n[[File:Bodleian Library MS. Arm. d.13. Armenian Gospels-0043-0.jpg|thumb|upright|Luke as depicted in the head-piece of an Armenian Gospel manuscript from 1609, held at the [[Bodleian Library]]]]\n\nThe composition of the writings, as well as the range of vocabulary used, indicate that the author was an educated man. A quote in the [[Epistle to the Colossians]] differentiates between Luke and other colleagues \"of the [[Circumcision controversy in early Christianity|circumcision]].\"\n\n{{quote|10 My fellow prisoner Aristarchus sends you his greetings, as does Mark, the cousin of Barnabas. 11 Jesus, who is called Justus, also sends greetings. These are the only Jews among my co-workers for the kingdom of God, and they have proved a comfort to me. ... 14 Our dear friend Luke, the doctor, and Demas send greetings. {{Bibleref|Colossians|4:10\u201311, 14}}.}}\n\nThis comment has traditionally caused commentators to conclude that Luke was a gentile. If this were true, it would make Luke the only writer of the New Testament who can clearly be identified as not being Jewish. However, that is not the only possibility. Although Luke is considered likely to have been a gentile Christian, some scholars believe him to have been a [[Hellenistic Jew|Hellenized Jew]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>Thomas S. McCall, Th.D. [http://www.levitt.com/essays/luke Was Luke a Gentile?]</ref> The phrase could just as easily be used to differentiate between those [[Jewish Christians|Christians who strictly observed the rituals of Judaism]] and those who did not.<ref name=EB/>\n\nLuke's presence in [[Rome]] with the Apostle Paul near the end of Paul's life was attested by 2 Timothy 4:11: \"Only Luke is with me\". In the last chapter of the Book of Acts, widely attributed to Luke, there are several accounts in the first person also affirming Luke's presence in Rome, including {{Bibleref|Acts|28:16}}: \"And when we came to Rome...\" According to some accounts,{{Which|date=September 2014}} Luke also contributed to the [[authorship of the Epistle to the Hebrews]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/07181a.htm|title=Catholic Encyclopedia: Epistle to the Hebrews|website=www.newadvent.org|access-date=2017-01-10}}</ref>\n\nLuke died at age 84 in [[Boeotia]], according to a \"fairly early and widespread tradition\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Butler's Lives of the Saints|last=|first=|publisher=HarperColllins Publishers|isbn=978-0-06-069299-5|editor-last=Walsh|editor-first=Michael|location=New York|date=5 July 1991|pages=[https://archive.org/details/butlerslivesofsa00butl/page/342 342]|url=https://archive.org/details/butlerslivesofsa00butl/page/342}}</ref> According to [[Nikephoros Kallistos Xanthopoulos]], Greek historian of the 14th century (and others), Luke's tomb was located in [[Thebes (Greece)|Thebes]], whence his relics were transferred to [[Constantinople]] in the year 357.<ref>'Ecclesiasticae Historiae Nicephori Callisti', Lib. II, Cap. XLIII, in J.P. Migne (ed.), ''Patrologia Graeca'' Vol. 145 (Paris 1901), [https://archive.org/stream/patrologicursus11migngoog#page/n441/mode/2up pp./cols. 875-878] (Internet Archive). (In Greek and Latin parallel).</ref>\n\n== Authorship of Luke and Acts ==\n{{see also|Authorship of Luke\u2013Acts}}\nThe Gospel of Luke does not name its author.<ref name=sanders>E. P. Sanders, ''The Historical Figure of Jesus'', (Penguin, 1995) pp. 63\u201364.</ref><ref name=ehrman>Bart D. Ehrman (2000:43) ''The New Testament: a historical introduction to early Christian writings.'' Oxford University Press.</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VrmW1eXBILgC&pg=PA328 |page=328 |title=Invitation to the Gospels |isbn=9780809140725 |last1=Senior |first1=Donald |last2=Achtemeier |first2=Paul J. |last3=Karris |first3=Robert J. |year=2002 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5SSytjasmAgC&pg=PA43 |page=43 |title=The Synoptic Gospels: An Introduction |isbn=9780664223496 |last1=Nickle |first1=Keith Fullerton |date=January 2001 }}</ref> The Gospel was not nor does it claim to be written by direct witnesses to the reported events, unlike Acts beginning in the sixteenth chapter.<ref name=lost>{{cite book |authorlink=Bart D. Ehrman |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=URdACxKubDIC&pg=PA235 |page=235 |title = Lost Christianities: The Battles for Scripture and the Faiths We Never Knew|isbn = 9780195182491|last1 = Ehrman|first1 = Bart D.|year = 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |authorlink=Bart D. Ehrman |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vbLK6kn5T-EC&pg=PA110 |page=110 |title = Truth and Fiction in the da Vinci Code: A Historian Reveals What We Really Know about Jesus, Mary Magdalene, and Constantine|isbn = 9780195346169|last1 = Ehrman|first1 = Bart D.|date = November 2004}}</ref><ref name=iuda>{{cite book |authorlink=Bart D. Ehrman |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oBuJMhJlTYwC&pg=PA143 |page=143 |title = The Lost Gospel of Judas Iscariot: A New Look at Betrayer and Betrayed|isbn = 9780199711048|last1 = Ehrman|first1 = Bart D.|date = 9 October 2006}}</ref> \n\nThe earliest manuscript of the Gospel (Papyrus 75 = Papyrus Bodmer XIV-XV), dated circa AD&nbsp;200, ascribes the work to Luke; as did [[Irenaeus]], writing circa AD&nbsp;180, and the [[Muratorian fragment]] from AD&nbsp;170.<ref>[[Raymond E. Brown|Brown, Raymond E.]] ''An Introduction to the New Testament'', p. 267. [[Anchor Bible]]; 1st edition (13 October 1997). {{ISBN|978-0-385-24767-2}}.</ref>\n\nThe gospel of Luke and the [[Acts of the Apostles]] make up a two-volume work which scholars call [[Luke\u2013Acts]]. Together they account for 27.5% of the [[New Testament]], the largest contribution by a single author.{{sfn|Boring|2012|p=556}}\n\n[[File:De heilige Lucas schildert de Madonna - Maarten van Heemskerck-1532.JPG|thumb|''Luke paints the Madonna and the Baby Jesus'', by [[Maarten van Heemskerck]], 1532]]\n\n== As a historian ==\n{{See also|Historical reliability of the Acts of the Apostles|Census of Quirinius|Chronology of Jesus}}\n[[File:Luke by roslin.jpg|thumb|upright|A medieval Armenian illumination of Luke, by [[Toros Roslin]]]]\nMost scholars understand Luke's works ([[Luke\u2013Acts]]) in the tradition of [[Greek historiography]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|chapter-url=http://religion-online.org/showchapter.asp?title=1116&C=1230|title=A Historical Introduction to the New Testament|last=Grant|first=Robert M.|publisher=Harper & Row|year=1963|chapter=Chapter 10: The Gospel of Luke and the Book of Acts|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100621102923/http://religion-online.org/showchapter.asp?title=1116&C=1230|archive-date=21 June 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> The preface of ''The Gospel of Luke''<ref name=preface>{{cite web | url = http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Luke%20(1:1-4)&version=NLT | title = Luke 1:1\u20134}}</ref> drawing on historical investigation identified the work to the readers as belonging to the genre of history.<ref>Richard Bauckham, ''Jesus and the Eyewitnesses''. 117.</ref> There is disagreement about how best to treat Luke's writings, with some historians{{who|date=February 2019}} regarding Luke as highly accurate, and others{{who|date=February 2019}} taking a more critical approach.\n\nBased on his accurate description of towns, cities and islands, as well as correctly naming various official titles, archaeologist [[William Mitchell Ramsay|Sir William Ramsay]] wrote that \"Luke is a historian of the first rank; not merely are his statements of fact trustworthy... [he] should be placed along with the very greatest of historians.\"<ref>Ramsay, ''The Bearing of Recent Discovery on the Trustworthiness of the New Testament'', 222, 1915</ref> Professor of Classics at [[Auckland University]], [[E.M. Blaiklock]], wrote: \"For accuracy of detail, and for evocation of atmosphere, Luke stands, in fact, with [[Thucydides]]. The Acts of the Apostles is not shoddy product of pious imagining, but a trustworthy record... it was the spadework of archaeology which first revealed the truth.\"<ref>Blaiklock, The Archaeology of the New Testament, p. 96, Zondervan Publishing Houst, Grand Rapids, Michigan, 1970.</ref> New Testament scholar Colin Hemer has made a number of advancements in understanding the historical nature and accuracy of Luke's writings.<ref>Hemer, \"The Book of Acts in the Setting of Hellenic History\", 104\u201307, as summarized by MacDowell.</ref>\n\nOn the purpose of Acts, New Testament Scholar [[Luke Timothy Johnson]] has noted that \"Luke's account is selected and shaped to suit his apologetic interests, not in defiance of but in conformity to ancient standards of historiography.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Johnson|first=Luke Timothy|authorlink=Luke Timothy Johnson|title=The Acts of the Apostles|publisher=The Liturgical Press|year=1992|pages=474\u201376|url= http://www.earlychristianwritings.com/luke.html}}</ref> Such a position is shared by most commentators such as Richard Heard who sees historical deficiencies as arising from \"special objects in writing and to the limitations of his sources of information.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Heard|first=Richard|title=An Introduction to the New Testament|chapter=13: The Acts of the Apostles|publisher=Harper & Brothers|year=1950|chapter-url=http://www.religion-online.org/showbook.asp?title=531|access-date=23 November 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620161529/http://religion-online.org/showbook.asp?title=531|archive-date=20 June 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring modern times, Luke's competence as a historian is questioned, depending upon one's ''a priori'' view of the supernatural.<ref name=\"markpowell\"/> Since post-[[Age of Enlightenment|Enlightenment]] historians work with [[methodological naturalism]],<ref>McGrew, Timothy, \"Miracles\", The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy (Winter 2015 Edition), Edward N. Zalta (ed.), http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/miracles/<br>Flew, Antony, 1966, ''God and Philosophy'', London: Hutchinson.<br>Ehrman, Bart D., 2003, ''The New Testament: A Historical Introduction to the Early Christian Writings'', 3rd ed., New York: Oxford University Press.<br>Bradley, Francis Herbert, 1874, \"The Presuppositions of Critical History,\" in ''Collected Essays'', vol. 1, Oxford, Clarendon Press, 1935.<br>McGrew's conclusion: historians work with [[methodological naturalism]], which precludes them from establishing miracles as objective historical facts (Flew 1966: 146; cf. Bradley 1874/1935; Ehrman 2003: 229).</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bringyou.to/apologetics/p96.htm|title=William Lane Craig and Bart Ehrman \"Is There Historical Evidence for the Resurrection of Jesus?\"|first1=Bart|last1=Ehrman|authorlink1=Bart D. Ehrman|first2=William Lane|last2=Craig|authorlink2=William Lane Craig|date=28 March 2006|publisher=bringyou.to|location=College of the Holy Cross, Worcester, Massachusetts|accessdate=11 August 2010|quote=Historians can only establish what probably happened in the past, and by definition a miracle is the least probable occurrence. And so, by the very nature of the canons of historical research, we can't claim historically that a miracle probably happened. By definition, it probably didn't. And history can only establish what probably did.}}</ref> such historians would see a narrative that relates supernatural, fantastic things like angels, demons etc., as problematic as a historical source. Mark Powell claims that \"it is doubtful whether the writing of history was ever Luke's intent. Luke wrote to proclaim, to persuade, and to interpret; he did not write to preserve records for posterity. An awareness of this, has been, for many, the final nail in Luke the historian's coffin.\"<ref name=\"markpowell\">{{cite book|last=Powell|first=Mark|title=What are they saying about Luke?|year=1989|publisher=Paulist Press|isbn=0-8091-3111-0|page=6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9jRu8_-GlKMC&pg=PA6 }}</ref>\n\nRobert M. Grant has noted that although Luke saw himself within the historical tradition, his work contains a number of statistical improbabilities, such as the sizable crowd addressed by Peter in Acts 4:4. He has also noted chronological difficulties whereby Luke \"has [[Gamaliel]] refer to [[Theudas]] and [[Judas of Galilee|Judas]] in the wrong order, and Theudas actually rebelled about a decade after Gamaliel spoke (5:36\u20137)\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== As an artist ==\n[[File:Evangelist Luka pishustchiy ikonu.jpg|thumb|upright|Luke the Evangelist painting the first [[icon]] of the Virgin Mary]]\nChristian tradition, starting from the 8th century, states that Luke was the first [[icon]] painter. He is said to have painted pictures of the [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Virgin Mary]] and Child, in particular the [[Hodegetria]] image in [[Constantinople]] (now lost). Starting from the 11th century, a number of painted images were venerated as his autograph works, including the [[Black Madonna of Cz\u0119stochowa]] and [[Theotokos of Vladimir|Our Lady of Vladimir]]. He was also said to have painted Saints [[Saint Peter|Peter]] and Paul, and to have illustrated a gospel book with a full cycle of miniatures.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grigg|first=Robert|date=1987|title=Byzantine Credulity as an Impediment to Antiquarianism|url=|journal=[[Gesta (journal)|Gesta]]|volume=26|issue=1|pages=3\u20139|doi=10.2307/767073|jstor=767073}}</ref><ref>The basic study on the legends concerning Saint Luke as a painter is Michele Bacci, Il pennello dell'Evangelista. Storia delle immagini sacre attribuite a san Luca (Pisa: Gisem, 1998).</ref>\n\nLate medieval [[Guild of Saint Luke|Guilds of Saint Luke]] in the cities of Late Medieval Europe, especially [[Flanders]], or the \"[[Accademia di San Luca]]\" (Academy of Saint Luke) in Rome\u2014imitated in many other European cities during the 16th century\u2014gathered together and protected painters. The tradition that Luke painted icons of Mary and Jesus has been common, particularly in [[Eastern Orthodoxy]]. The tradition also has support from the [[Saint Thomas Christians]] of India who claim to still have one of the [[Theotokos]] icons that Saint Luke painted and which St. Thomas brought to India.<ref>Father '''H. Hosten''' in his book ''Antiquities'' notes the following \"The picture at the mount is one of the oldest, and, therefore, one of the most venerable Christian paintings to be had in India. Other traditions hold that St. Luke painted two icons which currently are in Greece: the \"Theotokos Mega Spileotissa\" (Our Lady of the Great Cave, where supposedly Saint Luke lived for a period of time in asceticism) and the \"Panagia Soumela\", and \"Panagia Kykkou\" which are in Cyprus.\"</ref>\n\n== Symbol ==\n[[File:Hermen Rode 001.jpg|thumb|upright|Luke and the [[The Madonna|Madonna]], Altar of the Guild of Saint Luke, [[Hermen Rode]], [[L\u00fcbeck]] (1484)]]\nIn traditional depictions, such as paintings, [[evangelist portrait]]s, and church [[mosaic]]s, Saint Luke is often accompanied by an [[ox]] or [[bull]], usually having wings. Sometimes only the symbol is shown, especially when in a combination of those of all [[Four Evangelists]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Gospel Figures in Art|last=Zuffi|first=Stefano|publisher=Getty Publications|year=2003|isbn=0-89236-727-X|location=|pages=|chapter=The Evangelists and their symbols}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author1=George Ashdown Audsley |author2= William Audsley |title=Handbook of Christian Symbolism |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/handbookofchrist00auds |chapter=Chapter VI. Symbols and emblems of the Evangelists and the Apostles |year=1865}} Reprinted by Kessinger Publishing, 2003, {{ISBN|978-0-7661-5437-7}}.</ref>\n\n== Relics ==\nDespot [[\u0110ura\u0111 Brankovi\u0107|George of Serbia]] purportedly bought the relics from the Ottoman sultan [[Murad II]] for 30,000 gold coins. After the [[Ottoman conquest of Bosnia]], the kingdom's last queen, George's granddaughter [[Mary of Serbia, Queen of Bosnia|Mary]], who had brought the relics with her from Serbia as her dowry, sold them to the [[Venetian Republic]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Bosnian Church: A New Interpretation: A Study of the Bosnian Church and Its Place in State and Society from the 13th to the 15th Centuries|last=Van Antwerp Fine|first=John|publisher=East European Quarterly|year=1975|isbn=|location=|pages=331}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, the then [[Greek Orthodox]] Metropolitan [[Archbishop Ieronymos II of Athens|Ieronymos]] of [[Thebes, Greece|Thebes and Levathia]] (the current Archbishop of [[Athens]] and All Greece) requested from [[Diocese of Padua|Bishop Antonio Mattiazzo of Padua]] the return of \"a significant fragment of the relics of St. Luke to be placed on the site where the holy tomb of the Evangelist is located and venerated today\". This prompted a scientific investigation of the relics in [[Padua]], and by numerous lines of empirical evidence (archeological analyses of the Tomb in [[Thebes, Greece|Thebes]] and the Reliquary of [[Padua]], anatomical analyses of the remains, [[carbon-14 dating]], comparison with the purported skull of the Evangelist located in [[Prague]]) confirmed that these were the remains of an individual of Syrian descent who died between 416 BC and AD 72.<ref>V.T.W. Marin and F.G.B Trolese (eds.), ''San Luca evangelista testimone della fede che unisce. Atti del Congresso internazionale, Padova, 16-21 ottobre 2000 Volumes I-III'' (Padua: Istituto per la storia ecclesiastica Padovana, 2003). This is a three-volume work documenting the international congress in Padua in 2000 on the topic of Luke the evangelist, including his relics.</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/italy/1360095/DNA-test-pinpoints-St-Luke-the-apostles-remains-to-Padua.html|title=DNA test pinpoints St Luke the apostle's remains to Padua|last=Craig|first=Olga|date=21 October 2001|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=}}</ref> The [[Diocese of Padua|Bishop of Padua]] then delivered to Metropolitan Ieronymos the rib of Saint Luke that was closest to his heart to be kept at his tomb in Thebes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.traces-cl.com/archive/2000/novembre/luca.htm|title=The Beloved Physician|last=Tornielli|first=Andrea|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090607075349/http://www.traces-cl.com/archive/2000/novembre/luca.htm|archive-date=7 June 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/10/16/world/body-of-st-luke-gains-credibility.html|title=Body of St. Luke Gains Credibility|last=Wade|first=Nicholas|date=16 October 2001|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThus, the relics of Saint Luke are divided as follows:\n* The body, in the [[Abbey of Santa Giustina]] in Padua;\n* The head, in the [[St. Vitus Cathedral]] in Prague;\n* A rib, at his tomb in Thebes.\n\n==Gallery ==\n<gallery widths=\"154px\" heights=\"200px\" perrow=\"4\" caption=\"Luke the Evangelist\">\n\nFile:Luke_writing.jpg\nFile:142082810-612x612.jpg\nFile:Luke_the_Evangelist.jpg\nFile:Saint_luke.jpg\nFile:Nuremberg_chronicles_f_108r_1.png\nFile:Icon of the blessed Virgin Mary by Luke the Evangelist.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Wikipedia books|Gospel}}\n* [[John the Evangelist]]\n* [[Mark the Evangelist]]\n* [[Matthew the Apostle|Matthew the Evangelist]]\n\n== References and sources ==\n'''References'''\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n* Michele Bacci, ''Il pennello dell'Evangelista. Storia delle immagini sacre attribuite a san Luca'', Pisa: Gisem-Ets, 1998.\n* [[I. Howard Marshall]]. ''Luke: Historian and Theologian''. Downers Grove, Illinois: InterVarsity Press.\n* {{Cite book\n|last = Boring\n|first = M. Eugene\n|title = An Introduction to the New Testament: History, Literature, Theology\n|publisher = Westminster John Knox Press\n|year = 2012\n|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=leFrgkyEtusC&pg=PA556\n|ref = harv\n|isbn = 9780664255923\n}}\n* [[F. F. Bruce]], ''The Speeches in the Acts of the Apostles.'' London: The Tyndale Press, 1942.[http://www.biblicalstudies.org.uk/pdf/speeches_bruce.pdf ]\n* Helmut Koester. ''Ancient Christian Gospels''. Harrisburg, Pennsylvania: Trinity Press International, 1999.\n* Burton L. Mack. ''Who Wrote the New Testament?: The Making of the Christian Myth''. San Francisco, California: HarperCollins, 1996.\n* J. Wenham, \"The Identification of Luke\", ''[[Evangelical Quarterly]]'' 63 (1991), 3\u201344\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Luke the Evangelist}}\n{{AmCyc Poster|Luke, Saint|Luke the Evangelist}}\n* [http://www.allaboutthejourney.org/saint-luke.htm Biblical Interpretation of Texts of Saint Luke]\n* [http://www.earlychristianwritings.com/luke.html Early Christian Writings: ''Gospel of Luke'' e-texts, introductions]\n* [http://www.pnas.org/cgi/content/full/211540498v1?maxtoshow National Academy of Sciences on Luke the Evangelist]\n* [http://www.catholic.org/saints/saint.php?saint_id=76 Patron Saint Luke]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070311192236/http://www.glaubenswege.ch/Evangelist_Lukas.html Photo of the grave of Luke in Padua (in German)]\n* [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A05E6D61E3FF935A25753C1A9679C8B63 DNA testing of the Saint Luke corpse]\n* [http://www.santiebeati.it/dettaglio/21800, Santiebeati]\n* [http://www.catholic.org/saints/saint.php?saint_id=76, Catholic Online]\n\n{{New Testament people}}\n{{Gospel of Luke}}\n{{Acts of the Apostles}}\n{{Catholic saints}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Luke The Evangelist}}\n[[Category:84 deaths]]\n[[Category:1st-century Christian martyrs]]\n[[Category:1st-century Greek people]]\n[[Category:1st-century physicians]]\n[[Category:1st-century writers]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek physicians]]\n[[Category:Ancient Syrian physicians]]\n[[Category:Antiochian Greek Christians]]\n[[Category:Black Madonna of Cz\u0119stochowa]]\n[[Category:Christianity in Roman Achaea]]\n[[Category:Gospel of Luke]]\n[[Category:Saints from Roman Anatolia]]\n[[Category:People in Acts of the Apostles]]\n[[Category:People in the Pauline epistles]]\n[[Category:Seventy disciples]]\n[[Category:Saints from Roman Syria]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Four Evangelists]]\n[[Category:Burials at the Church of the Holy Apostles]]\n[[Category:Burials in Greece]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luke_the_Evangelist"}
{"title_page": "Arthur R. M. Spaid", "text_new": "{{short description|American educator, school administrator, lecturer, and writer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix =\n|name         = Arthur R. M. Spaid\n|honorific-suffix =\n|image        = Arthur R. M. Spaid.jpg\n|caption      = Portrait of Spaid from ''History of Hampshire County, West Virginia'' (1897)\n|alt          =\n|office = [[Delaware Department of Education|Delaware State Commissioner of Education]]\n|term_start   = July 1, 1917\n|term_end     = July 1, 1921\n|predecessor  =\n|successor    =\n|office2 = Superintendent of [[Dorchester County Public Schools]]\n|term_start2   = 1913\n|term_end2    = 1917\n|predecessor2  =\n|successor2   =\n|office3 = Superintendent of [[New Castle County, Delaware|New Castle County]] Public Schools\n|term_start3   = 1903\n|term_end3    = 1913\n|predecessor3  =\n|successor3   =\n|office4 = Principal of [[Alexis I. duPont High School]]\n|term_start4   = 1894\n|term_end4    = 1903\n|predecessor4  =\n|successor4   =\n|birth_date= {{Birth date|1866|07|27}}\n|birth_place=[[Capon Springs, West Virginia]], United States\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|1936|03|16|1866|07|27}}\n|death_place=[[Winchester, Virginia]], United States\n|resting_place=\n|alma_mater=[[Wilmington College (Ohio)|Wilmington College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|AB]])<br />[[Haverford College]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])<br />[[Columbia University]] (MA)\n|profession= [[educator]], school administrator, [[Superintendent (education)|superintendent]], and education commissioner\n|spouse= Mary Abi Farquhar Spaid\n|children=\n|relations=John W. Spaid (father)<br />Margaret Elizabeth Brill Spaid (mother)<ref name=\"The Washington Herald 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Woman of Seventy Expires. | newspaper = [[The Washington Herald]] | location = Washington, D.C. | date = January 13, 1910 | page = 9 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83045433/1910-01-13/ed-1/seq-9.pdf | accessdate = February 20, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220220557/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83045433/1910-01-13/ed-1/seq-9.pdf | archive-date = February 20, 2019}}</ref>\n|residence=\n}}\n\n'''Arthur Rusmiselle Miller Spaid''' (July 27, 1866 \u2013 March 16, 1936) was an American educator, school administrator, lecturer, and writer. He served as principal of [[Alexis I. duPont High School]] (1894\u20131903) in [[Wilmington, Delaware]], superintendent of [[New Castle County, Delaware|New Castle County]] Public Schools (1903\u20131913) in Delaware, superintendent of [[Dorchester County Public Schools]] (1913\u20131917) in Maryland, and [[Delaware Department of Education|Delaware State commissioner of Education]] (1917\u20131921).\n\nIn 1894, Spaid relocated to Delaware, where he was elected principal of Alexis I. duPont High School in Wilmington and served in this position until 1903. Spaid became superintendent of New Castle County Public Schools in 1903 and remained in this position until 1913. Throughout his tenure as superintendent, Spaid argued for compulsory education and the consolidation of New Castle County's rural public schools. In response to a shortage of teachers, Spaid instituted pay raises for some teachers in July 1906 so that they would return for the fall term. In May 1908, the Delaware State Board of Education appointed Spaid and the county superintendents to a committee charged with revising the state public school system's curriculum.\n\nSpaid received a Master of Arts degree in education from [[Columbia University]] in 1917. In November 1918, he issued a bulletin entitled, ''Our Children Must Be Educated'', in which he appealed to parents and school administrators to address rising teacher resignations, withdrawals of school children and other conditions that affected the state's public school system. He stressed that it was necessary to keep Delaware's children in school to avoid illiteracy. Under Spaid's initiative to bring efficiency to the state's public school system, the Delaware State Board of Education adopted a new school code in 1919. In May 1921, Spaid and the State Board of Education urged county superintendents and school principals to observe [[Memorial Day]] at their schools. Spaid left Delaware in 1921 and engaged in [[Chautauqua]]-related work before becoming the head of the Education Department at [[Salem University]] in [[Salem, West Virginia]], from 1926 to 1936.\n\nSpaid was a [[Natural history|naturalist]] by hobby and took hundreds of photographs, using them to illustrate his nature study articles and lecture slides. Throughout his career as a school administrator, Spaid also served as an instructor, lecturer, and speaker for multiple courses, institutes, and organizations. Spaid was also an avid writer, and he published articles in ''[[Scientific American]]'' and ''[[Country Life in America]]''. Spaid had planned to author a book on his nature studies, for which he had written notes and collected specimens; however, his home and notebooks were destroyed in a fire in 1917. Spaid died at the home of his daughter in [[Winchester, Virginia]], in 1936. According to historians [[Hu Maxwell]] and [[Howard Llewellyn Swisher]], Spaid \"placed himself in the front rank of the educational works of Delaware, and received the commendation of the press and the educators for his advanced ideas.\"<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\">{{Harvnb|Maxwell|Swisher|1897|p=730.}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nArthur Rusmiselle Miller Spaid was born on 27&nbsp;July 1866 in [[Capon Springs, West Virginia|Capon Springs]], West Virginia, to John W. Spaid and his wife, Margaret Elizabeth Brill Spaid.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"Secrest 1\">{{Harvnb|Secrest|1922|p=65.}}</ref><ref name=\"The Morning News 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = A. R. M. Spaid Dies In Virginia; Once School Head Here | newspaper = [[The News Journal|Wilmington Morning News]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = March 17, 1936 | page = 1 | url = https://www.newspapers.com/image/154511419/ | accessdate = November 4, 2018 | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | archive-url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25098939/a_r_m_spaid_dies_in_virginia_once/ | archive-date = November 4, 2018}}</ref> Arthur Spaid was the eldest of six children, with two brothers and three sisters: Luther Lore \"Boyd\" Spaid (1868\u20131877), Elia May Spaid (1870\u20131911), Martha Evalona Spaid (1875\u20131921), William Pohe Spaid (1878\u20131885), and Eleanor \"Nellie\" Love Spaid (1881\u2013unknown).<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/> His great-great-grandfather, George Nicholas Spaid (n\u00e9 Spaht), originated from [[Kassel]], Germany, and settled in [[Hampshire County, West Virginia|Hampshire County]] along the [[Cacapon River]] in the late 18th century.<ref name=\"Maxwell 2\">{{Harvnb|Maxwell|Swisher|1897|p=729.}}</ref><ref name=\"Secrest 4\">{{Harvnb|Secrest|1922|pp=5\u20137.}}</ref> Spaid's parents raised their family on a small farm on [[Timber Ridge]].<ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/> His father was a [[Shoemaking|shoemaker]] who was interested in literature and recorded local history in notebooks.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/> \n\nSpaid received his primary and secondary education in the [[Hampshire County Schools|public schools of Hampshire County]] and worked on his family's farm until the age of 20.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\">{{cite newspaper | title = Delaware Men of Affairs | newspaper = [[The News Journal|The Evening Journal]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = January 25, 1919 | page = 14 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_hockessin_ver01/data/sn85042354/00383343033/1919012501/0900.pdf | accessdate = September 14, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190914232942/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_hockessin_ver01/data/sn85042354/00383343033/1919012501/0900.pdf | archive-date = September 14, 2019}}</ref> He completed his primary education in 1886 and earned his teaching certificate shortly thereafter. In the spring of 1886, he attended Professor Taylor's private school in [[Lacey Spring, Virginia]], for three months and won prizes in spelling and history while there.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> Throughout his early education, Spaid was active in \"scholastic athletics,\" including corner ball, [[baseball]], running, and jumping.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> In the summer of 1886, Spaid briefly attended Professor Borglebaugh's [[normal school]] in nearby [[Broadway, Virginia]].<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/> He completed his teacher's examination shortly thereafter and earned his [[Certified teacher|teaching certificate]].<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/>\n\n== Career ==\n=== Teaching and librarian ===\nIn 1886, Spaid began his first teaching position at the rural Loan Oak School in Broadway; he remained there until 1887.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 2\">{{cite newspaper | title = A. R. M. Spaid Dies In Virginia; Once School Head Here | newspaper = [[The News Journal|Wilmington Morning News]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = March 17, 1936 | page = 2 | url = https://www.newspapers.com/image/154511438/ | accessdate = February 2, 2019 | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | archive-url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27954171/a_r_m_spaid_dies_in_virginia_once/ | archive-date = February 2, 2019}}</ref> During his time in Broadway, he was a member of the Broadway Literary Society.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> Spaid visited [[Washington Court House, Ohio|Washington, Ohio]], at his cousin's invitation.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/> He entered Washington College and subsequently resigned from his teaching position in Virginia.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/> To support himself during his first year in Washington, Spaid served as the college's assistant librarian and as the librarian of the town's [[Woman's Christian Temperance Union]] library.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/> During this time he lived on two to three dollars per month, and was a bachelor.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/> The following year, Spaid took on the role of the [[Sexton (office)|sexton]] of the Christian Church.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/>\n\n=== School administration ===\nFrom 1889 to 1890, Spaid served as the principal of [[Twin Township, Ross County, Ohio|Twin Township]] High School in [[Bourneville, Ohio]].<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/> From 1890 to 1891, he was principal of Bourneville's graded schools.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> While in Bourneville he economized by residing with village school teacher E. M. Parrett.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/> Spaid reentered college in 1891, but the illness and death of his brother-in-law Carter Gilbert Kelso caused him to return to Bourneville to complete Kelso's term at school.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name = \"Harloe 1\">{{Harvnb|Harloe|1943|p=222.}}</ref> After completing Kelso's term, Spaid returned to his studies, finished his course in 1893, and earned his [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree from [[Wilmington College (Ohio)|Wilmington College]] in [[Wilmington, Ohio]], where he was president of his class and participated in the Dorian Literary Society.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/>\n\nDuring his senior year at Wilmington College, Spaid was awarded the $500 Haverford Fellowship, which allowed him to pursue a year of post-graduate work at [[Haverford College]] in [[Haverford, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> He returned to [[Concord, Hampshire County, West Virginia|Concord]] in Hampshire County, West Virginia, and then entered Haverford College in 1893.<ref name=\"Thomas 1\">{{Harvnb|Thomas|1900|p=277.}}</ref> Spaid completed his graduate studies in American history and earned a [[Master of Arts]] degree from Haverford College in 1894.<ref name=\"The Morning News 1\"/><ref name=\"Thomas 1\"/><ref name=\"Haverford College 1\">{{Harvnb|Haverford College|1905|p=60.}}</ref>\n\nSpaid relocated to Delaware in 1894<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> and was elected principal of [[Alexis I. duPont High School]] in [[Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington]].<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/><ref name=\"Thomas 1\"/> According to historians [[Hu Maxwell]] and [[Howard Llewellyn Swisher]], Spaid \"placed himself in the front rank of the educational works of Delaware and received the commendation of the press and the educators for his advanced ideas.\"<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/> While serving as the high school's principal, he and his family resided in the Highlands neighborhood of Wilmington.<ref name=\"Thomas 1\"/> In June 1897, at the end of the school year, the school's students presented Spaid with a traveling case.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 8\">{{cite newspaper | title = Good-Bye School Days | newspaper = [[The News Journal|The Evening Journal]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = June 24, 1897 | page = 1 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_bear_ver01/data/sn85042354/00383343392/1897062401/0570.pdf | accessdate = August 18, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190819020301/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_bear_ver01/data/sn85042354/00383343392/1897062401/0570.pdf | archive-date = August 18, 2019}}</ref> He served as the principal of Alexis I. duPont High School until 1903.<ref name=\"The Morning News 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/>\n\n=== Superintendent of county public schools ===\nSpaid was the Superintendent of [[New Castle County, Delaware|New Castle County]] Public Schools from 1903 to 1913.<ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> While serving as superintendent, he resided in [[Brandywine, Delaware|Brandywine]].<ref name=\"The Middletown Transcript 2\">{{cite newspaper | title = State Board of Education | newspaper = The Middletown Transcript | location = [[Middletown, Delaware]] | date = November 19, 1904 | page = 2 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84026820/1904-11-19/ed-1/seq-2.pdf | accessdate = February 3, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190203230515/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84026820/1904-11-19/ed-1/seq-2.pdf | archive-date = February 3, 2019}}</ref> He was one of three county superintendents in Delaware; the other two administered the public schools in [[Kent County, Delaware|Kent]] and [[Sussex County, Delaware|Sussex]] counties.<ref name=\"The Middletown Transcript 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Consolidate Rural Schools | newspaper = The Middletown Transcript | location = [[Middletown, Delaware]] | date = January 28, 1905 | page = 2 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84026820/1905-01-28/ed-1/seq-2.pdf | accessdate = February 3, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190203222016/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84026820/1905-01-28/ed-1/seq-2.pdf | archive-date = February 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November 1904, a special session of the Delaware State Board of Education appointed Spaid and the other two county superintendents to a committee charged with proposing and explaining legislation to improve and modernize the state's public school system to the [[Delaware Senate]] and [[Delaware House of Representatives]].<ref name=\"The Middletown Transcript 2\"/> \n\nThroughout his tenure as superintendent, Spaid argued for compulsory education and the consolidation of the county's rural public schools. At a legislative conference on education in January 1905, Spaid and the other two county superintendents urged the consolidation of Delaware's rural schools to improve the education of students in the state's more isolated areas.<ref name=\"The Middletown Transcript 1\"/> Spaid declared at the conference that he would require greater influence if he were to be reappointed as superintendent.<ref name=\"The Middletown Transcript 1\"/> He stated that \"if the position of superintendent of free schools was not worth awarding on merit alone&nbsp;... then he wanted to get out.\"<ref name=\"The Middletown Transcript 1\"/> He emphasized the necessity for graded consolidated schools in rural areas of New Castle County.<ref name=\"The Middletown Transcript 1\"/> Spaid noted that some of the county's rural schools had only one student in attendance for weeks at a time during the school year, and because of this the county's public schools were wasting money and the children in those affected areas were growing up in \"ignorance\".<ref name=\"The Middletown Transcript 1\"/> Spaid concluded that \"compulsory education and consolidation of the schools was needed.\"<ref name=\"The Middletown Transcript 1\"/>\n\nIn response to a shortage of teachers, Spaid instituted pay raises for some teachers in July 1906 so they would return for the fall term.<ref name=\"Cecil Whig 2\">{{cite newspaper | title = News in Brief | newspaper = [[Cecil Whig]] | location = [[Elkton, Maryland]] | date = July 28, 1906 | page = 3 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83016348/1906-07-28/ed-1/seq-3.pdf | accessdate = February 3, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190203212129/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83016348/1906-07-28/ed-1/seq-3.pdf | archive-date = February 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSpaid's support of [[Prohibition in the United States|prohibition]] brought him into conflict with Wilmington's [[German Americans|German American]] community.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 3\">{{cite newspaper | title = German Citizens Score Mr. Spaid | newspaper = [[The News Journal|The Evening Journal]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = August 30, 1907 | page = 6 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1907-08-30/ed-1/seq-6.pdf | accessdate = February 20, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220144727/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1907-08-30/ed-1/seq-6.pdf | archive-date = February 20, 2019}}</ref> In 1907, Spaid received a letter from William J. Hogan who inquired about his position on prohibition.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 3\"/> According to Wilmington's German American community, Spaid's response to the letter made \"insulting remarks\" about the unreliability of immigrants who drank beer.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 3\"/> The local [[National German-American Alliance|German-American Alliance]] held a public meeting at a [[Turners|Turn Hall]] regarding Spaid's letter and addressed an open letter to him in which the alliance noted the academic achievements of Germans and the low literacy rates in prohibition states.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 3\"/>\n\nIn May 1908, the Delaware State Board of Education appointed Spaid and the county superintendents to a committee charged with revising the state public school system's curriculum.<ref name=\"Cecil Whig 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = News in Brief | newspaper = [[Cecil Whig]] | location = [[Elkton, Maryland]] | date = May 23, 1908 | page = 3 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83016348/1908-05-23/ed-1/seq-3.pdf | accessdate = February 3, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190203211301/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83016348/1908-05-23/ed-1/seq-3.pdf | archive-date = February 3, 2019}}</ref> In 1913, Spaid was named superintendent of [[Dorchester County Public Schools]] in nearby [[Dorchester County, Maryland]].<ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/>\n\nIn July 1914, Spaid was elected Supervisor of [[Washington County, Maryland]], schools and assumed his duties in August 1914.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 10\">{{cite newspaper | title = New Place for Prof. Spaid. | newspaper = [[The News Journal|The Evening Journal]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = July 24, 1914 | page = 6 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_fairfax_ver01/data/sn85042354/00383343057/1914072401/1003.pdf | accessdate = September 13, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190913200124/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_fairfax_ver01/data/sn85042354/00383343057/1914072401/1003.pdf | archive-date = September 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSpaid received a Master of Arts degree in education from [[Columbia University]] in 1917.<ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/> While at Columbia, Spaid completed a course in \"school administration and supervision\" and was a member of the university's Administration Club.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> In addition to his Master of Arts degree, Columbia also conferred upon Spaid the title of \"Superintendent of Schools\".<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/>\n\n=== State Commissioner of Delaware Education ===\n[[File:Delaware Men of Affairs.jpg|thumb|right|Sketch portrait of Spaid from ''The Evening Journal'' (1919).]]\nFrom 1&nbsp;July 1917 until 1&nbsp;July 1921, Spaid served as the [[Delaware Department of Education|Delaware State Commissioner of Education]],<ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> during which time he resided with his family at 241 North State Street in [[Dover, Delaware|Dover]].<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/><ref name=\"Newark Post 4\">{{cite newspaper | title = Personals | newspaper = [[Newark Post]] | location = [[Newark, Delaware]] | date = May 28, 1919 | page = 5 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1919-05-28/ed-1/seq-5.pdf | accessdate = February 3, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190203204210/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1919-05-28/ed-1/seq-5.pdf | archive-date = February 3, 2019}}</ref> Philanthropist [[Pierre S. du Pont]] was secretary of the Delaware State Board of Education while Spaid served in this position.<ref name=\"Newark Post 7\">{{cite newspaper | title = State Board of Education Here Friday | newspaper = [[Newark Post]] | location = [[Newark, Delaware]] | date = October 1, 1919 | page = 8 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1919-10-01/ed-1/seq-8.pdf | accessdate = February 20, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220175834/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1919-10-01/ed-1/seq-8.pdf | archive-date = February 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1918, Spaid held meetings of the Delaware State Board of Education at [[Stanton, Delaware|Stanton]] and locations across Delaware to hear from residents in school districts affected by the [[Delaware General Assembly]]'s 1915 alteration of school district boundaries, to include consolidation of districts.<ref name=\"Newark Post 6\">{{cite newspaper | title = State Board Meeting at Stanton | newspaper = [[Newark Post]] | location = [[Newark, Delaware]] | date = May 8, 1918 | page = 5 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1918-05-08/ed-1/seq-5.pdf | accessdate = February 20, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220170320/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1918-05-08/ed-1/seq-5.pdf | archive-date = February 20, 2019}}</ref> As state commissioner, he convened a State Teachers' Institute in [[Newark, Delaware|Newark]] in August 1918.<ref name=\"Newark Post 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Institute Closed Friday | newspaper = [[Newark Post]] | location = [[Newark, Delaware]] | date = August 28, 1918 | page = 1 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1918-08-28/ed-1/seq-1.pdf | accessdate = February 3, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190203200528/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1918-08-28/ed-1/seq-1.pdf | archive-date = February 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring his tenure as state commissioner, Delaware's public school system was impacted by [[World War I]] and the [[Spanish flu|1918 influenza pandemic]]. The pandemic caused Delaware's State Board of Health to shutter the state's public schools for three to four weeks.<ref name=\"Newark Post 5\">{{cite newspaper | title = Our Children Must Be Educated | newspaper = [[Newark Post]] | location = [[Newark, Delaware]] | date = November 27, 1918 | page = 7 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1918-11-27/ed-1/seq-7.pdf | accessdate = February 3, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190203215056/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1918-11-27/ed-1/seq-7.pdf | archive-date = February 3, 2019}}</ref> In November 1918, Spaid issued a four-page bulletin entitled, ''Our Children Must Be Educated'', in which he appealed to parents and school administrators to address rising teacher resignations, school children withdrawals and other conditions affecting the state's public school system.<ref name=\"Newark Post 5\"/> In his bulletin, Spaid commended the work of [[Liberty bond]] campaigns and War Work drives.<ref name=\"Newark Post 5\"/> In addition, he stated, \"This great world war is being fought to make democracy safe, but a democracy to be safe must be composed of intelligent citizens.\"<ref name=\"Newark Post 5\"/> He stressed that it was necessary to keep Delaware's children in school to avoid illiteracy.<ref name=\"Newark Post 5\"/> He concluded his bulletin by stating, \"Let us make still one more 'drive,' and 'go over the top' for an efficient school system, thus laying the everlasting foundation of a government in which democracy will be safe.\"<ref name=\"Newark Post 5\"/>\n\nUnder Spaid's initiative to bring efficiency to the state's public school system, the Delaware State Board of Education adopted a new school code in 1919.<ref name=\"Newark Post 3\">{{cite newspaper | title = Commissioner of Education Explains Code | newspaper = [[Newark Post]] | location = [[Newark, Delaware]] | date = July 2, 1919 | page = 4 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1919-07-02/ed-1/seq-4.pdf | accessdate = February 3, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190203201916/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1919-07-02/ed-1/seq-4.pdf | archive-date = February 3, 2019}}</ref> According to Spaid its purpose was to provide an equal education for all Delaware students.<ref name=\"Newark Post 3\"/> He also noted that the code addressed the problem of illiteracy, which had been discovered by [[draft board]]s during World War I,<ref name=\"Newark Post 3\"/> and that the code sought to integrate all of Delaware's public schools into a coordinated state system.<ref name=\"Newark Post 3\"/> In May 1921, Spaid and the State Board of Education urged county superintendents and school principals to observe [[Memorial Day]] at their schools, in coordination with local [[Grand Army of the Republic]], [[United Spanish War Veterans]], and [[World War Veterans]] organizations.<ref name=\"Newark Post 2\">{{cite newspaper | title = Asks Schools to Celebrate Memorial Day | newspaper = [[Newark Post]] | location = [[Newark, Delaware]] | date = May 25, 1921 | page = 3 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1921-05-25/ed-1/seq-3.pdf | accessdate = February 3, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190203200455/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1921-05-25/ed-1/seq-3.pdf | archive-date = February 3, 2019}}</ref> Spaid and the state board also recommended that school children bring flowers from home, place them at veterans' graves in local cemeteries, and be dismissed for the remainder of the school day.<ref name=\"Newark Post 2\"/> Spaid resigned as Delaware's State Commissioner of Education in 1921.<ref name=\"Normal Instructor 1\">{{cite journal | title = Educational Notes | newspaper = Normal Instructor and Primary Plans | publisher = F.A. Owen Publishing Company | location = [[Dansville, Livingston County, New York|Dansville, New York]] | date = September 1921 | volume = XXX | issue = 9 | page = 16 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=H1M5AQAAMAAJ | accessdate = February 16, 2020 | via = [[Google Books]] }}</ref>\n\n=== Later years ===\nIn 1921, after resigning as Delaware's State Commissioner of Education, Spaid left Delaware and began engaging in [[Chautauqua]]-related work.<ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/> Around 1926, he became head of the Education Department at [[Salem University]] in [[Salem, West Virginia]], and served in this position until 1936.<ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/>\n\n== Lecturer and writer ==\nSpaid was a [[Natural history|naturalist]] by hobby.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/> He took hundreds of photographs of objects in nature, and used these photographs to illustrate his nature study articles and lecture slides.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/>\n\nThroughout his career as a school administrator, Spaid also served as an instructor, lecturer, and speaker for multiple courses, institutes, and organizations. In 1900 and 1902, Spaid delivered illustrated lectures for the Natural History Society of Delaware at the [[Wilmington Friends School]] on the topics of \"The Historic and Picturesque [[Shenandoah Valley]]\",<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Lectured on Shenandoah Valley | newspaper = [[The News Journal|The Evening Journal]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = May 26, 1900 | page = 4 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1900-05-26/ed-1/seq-4.pdf | accessdate = February 4, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190204005407/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1900-05-26/ed-1/seq-4.pdf | archive-date = February 4, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"The Wilmington Daily Republican 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Educational Matters. | newspaper = The Wilmington Daily Republican | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = May 23, 1900 | page = 4 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_fidelius_ver01/data/sn88053055/00271741248/1900052301/0509.pdf | accessdate = September 13, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190913200558/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_fidelius_ver01/data/sn88053055/00271741248/1900052301/0509.pdf | archive-date = September 13, 2019}}</ref> \"Eggs and Feathers\",<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 7\">{{cite newspaper | title = Mr. Spaid to Lecture | newspaper = [[The News Journal|The Evening Journal]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = January 9, 1902 | page = 5 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1902-01-09/ed-1/seq-5.pdf | accessdate = February 20, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220203506/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1902-01-09/ed-1/seq-5.pdf | archive-date = February 20, 2019}}</ref> and \"Leaves and Blossoms.\"<ref name=\"The Evening Republican 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Dots. | newspaper = The Evening Republican | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = April 11, 1902 | page = 1 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053043/1902-04-11/ed-1/seq-1.pdf | accessdate = February 20, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220184703/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053043/1902-04-11/ed-1/seq-1.pdf | archive-date = February 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 4\">{{cite newspaper | title = Local News Notes | newspaper = [[The News Journal|The Evening Journal]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = April 2, 1900 | page = 1 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1900-04-02/ed-1/seq-1.pdf | accessdate = February 20, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220190415/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1900-04-02/ed-1/seq-1.pdf | archive-date = February 20, 2019}}</ref> In 1901, Spaid delivered a lecture on reptiles entitled \"Fangs, Fins and Stings\" in the [[Breck's Mill Area]] of Wilmington,<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 2\">{{cite newspaper | title = Lectured on Reptiles | newspaper = [[The News Journal|The Evening Journal]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = November 16, 1901 | page = 1 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1901-11-16/ed-1/seq-1.pdf | accessdate = February 4, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190204014658/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1901-11-16/ed-1/seq-1.pdf | archive-date = February 4, 2019}}</ref> and in February and April 1904, he presented a lecture tour across northern Delaware with illustrated lectures on \"Eggs and Feathers\", \"The Picturesque Luray Caverns\", and \"Historic Shenandoah Valley.\"<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 5\">{{cite newspaper | title = Spaid to Lecture. | newspaper = [[The News Journal|The Evening Journal]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = February 12, 1904 | page = 3 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1904-02-12/ed-1/seq-3.pdf | accessdate = February 20, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220190949/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1904-02-12/ed-1/seq-3.pdf | archive-date = February 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 6\">{{cite newspaper | title = Lectures by Prof. Spaid. | newspaper = [[The News Journal|The Evening Journal]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = April 11, 1904 | page = 5 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1904-04-11/ed-1/seq-5.pdf | accessdate = February 20, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220193059/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1904-04-11/ed-1/seq-5.pdf | archive-date = February 20, 2019}}</ref> Between 1903 and 1905, Spaid gave 100 lectures to around 10,000 people,<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 9\">{{cite newspaper | title = Gave Many Free Lectures. | newspaper = [[The News Journal|The Evening Journal]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = July 31, 1905 | page = 5 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_christiana_ver01/data/sn85042354/00383343513/1905073101/1182.pdf | accessdate = September 13, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190913193734/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_christiana_ver01/data/sn85042354/00383343513/1905073101/1182.pdf | archive-date = September 13, 2019}}</ref> including a new lecture entitled, \"Delaware, Nesting Place of the Blue Hen's Chickens\".<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 9\"/> In April 1911, at a meeting of rural New Castle County teachers in Wilmington Spaid delivered a speech on birds.<ref name=\"Newark Post 8\">{{cite newspaper | title = County Teachers Entertained | newspaper = [[Newark Post]] | location = [[Newark, Delaware]] | date = April 26, 1911 | page = 3 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1911-04-26/ed-1/seq-3.pdf | accessdate = February 20, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220194956/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1911-04-26/ed-1/seq-3.pdf | archive-date = February 20, 2019}}</ref> In November 1917, he addressed the annual convention of the Delaware Woman's Christian Temperance Union in [[Seaford, Delaware|Seaford]] on the importance of [[Department of Scientific Temperance Instruction|scientific temperance instruction]] in public schools.<ref name=\"The Union Signal 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Patriotism and Suffrage Live Topics at Delaware Convention | newspaper = The Union Signal | location = [[Evanston, Illinois]] | date = November 15, 1917 | page = 13 | url = https://archive.org/details/unionsignaljourn43woma/page/n705 | accessdate = February 21, 2019 | via = [[Internet Archive]] | archive-url = | archive-date = }}</ref> In June 1919, Spaid held an open-air meeting on faith and asserted that \"one outstanding result\" of World War I \"was a return to elemental Christian faith.\"<ref name=\"Newark Post 9\">{{cite newspaper | title = First Of Open Air Meetings Held Sunday Night | newspaper = [[Newark Post]] | location = [[Newark, Delaware]] | date = June 18, 1919 | page = 1 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1919-06-18/ed-1/seq-1.pdf | accessdate = February 20, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220205623/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1919-06-18/ed-1/seq-1.pdf | archive-date = February 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring his tenure as New Castle County superintendent, Spaid delivered 100 lectures in the county's schools.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> He was an instructor and lecturer for the Delaware State Summer School for 11 years, and for the Maryland State Summer School for two years.<ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/> He served as a Sunday speaker for the [[temperance movement]] [[Anti-Saloon League]] in Delaware, Maryland, New York, and Pennsylvania for several years.<ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/> In addition, Spaid was a lecturer in the People's Course at [[Newark, New Jersey]], for five years,<ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/> and was a lecturer at teachers' institutes in Delaware, Indiana, Maryland, New Jersey, Ohio, and Pennsylvania.<ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/><ref name=\"Secrest 2\">{{Harvnb|Secrest|1922|pp=65\u201366.}}</ref>\n\n=== Publications ===\nIn addition to public speaking, Spaid was an avid writer.<ref name=\"Secrest 3\">{{Harvnb|Secrest|1922|p=66.}}</ref> His articles on the subjects of history and nature included:<ref name=\"Secrest 3\"/>\n* {{cite magazine\n| date        = March\u2013August 1895\n| title       = Slavery in Pennsylvania\n| magazine    = The American Historical Register and Monthly Gazette of the Patriotic\u2013Hereditary Societies of the United States of America\n| location    = Philadelphia\n| publisher   = The Historical Register Publishing Company\n| oclc        = 565053224\n| volume      = ii\n| pages       = 1181\u20131187\n| url         = https://archive.org/details/americanhistoricv2brow/page/1180\n}}<ref name=\"The Record-Union 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = New Publications. | newspaper = [[The Sacramento Union|Sacramento Daily Record-Union]] | location = [[Sacramento, California]] | date = July 12, 1895 | page = 4 | url = https://www.newspapers.com/image/42201518/ | accessdate = February 3, 2019 | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | archive-url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27961540/new_publications/ | archive-date = February 3, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"The Pittsburgh Post 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Slavery in Pennsylvania. | newspaper = [[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette#Post|The Pittsburgh Post]] | location = [[Pittsburgh]] | date = July 14, 1895 | page = 4 | url = https://www.newspapers.com/image/86406505/ | accessdate = February 3, 2019 | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | archive-url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27985609/slavery_in_pennsylvania/ | archive-date = February 3, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Wiley 1\">{{Harvnb|Wiley|Rines|1913|p=168.}}</ref>\n* {{cite magazine\n| date        = November 14, 1903\n| title       = Some of Our Common Snakes.\u2014I.\n| magazine    = [[Scientific American]]\n| issn        = 0036-8733\n| pages       = 352\u2013353\n| volume      = 89\n| issue       = 20\n| publisher   = Munn and Company\n| location    = New York\n| url         = https://archive.org/details/scientific-american-1903-11-14/page/n17\n| via         =\n}}<ref name=\"Scientific American 1\">{{cite magazine\n |date         = November 14, 1903\n |title        = Some of Our Common Snakes.\u2014I.\n |magazine     = [[Scientific American]]\n |issn         = 0036-8733\n |pages        = 352\u2013353\n |volume       = 89\n |issue        = 20\n |publisher    = Munn and Company\n |location     = New York\n |url          = https://archive.org/details/scientific-american-1903-11-14/\n |via          = [[Internet Archive]]\n |access-date  = February 21, 2019\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170324021659/https://archive.org/details/scientific-american-1903-11-14\n |archive-date = March 24, 2017\n |url-status   = live\n}}</ref>\n* {{cite magazine\n| date        = 1904\n| title       = Harmless Little Reptile\n| magazine    = [[Scientific American]]\n| issn        = 0036-8733\n}}<ref name=\"The St. Tammany Farmer 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Harmless Little Reptile. | newspaper = The St. Tammany Farmer | location = [[Covington, Louisiana]] | date = April 23, 1904 | page = 6 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015387/1904-04-23/ed-1/seq-6.pdf | accessdate = February 20, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220183147/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015387/1904-04-23/ed-1/seq-6.pdf | archive-date = February 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Williston Graphic 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Harmless Little Reptile. | newspaper = Williston Graphic | location = [[Williston, North Dakota]] | date = April 28, 1904 | page = 6 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88076270/1904-04-28/ed-1/seq-6.pdf | accessdate = February 20, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220182302/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88076270/1904-04-28/ed-1/seq-6.pdf | archive-date = February 20, 2019}}</ref>\n* {{cite magazine\n| date        = December 1907\n| title       = Among the Holly Gatherers\n| url         = https://books.google.com/books?id=l4U3AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA230\n| magazine    = [[Country Life in America]]\n| location    = New York\n| publisher   = [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday, Page & Company]]\n| oclc        = 844607264\n| volume      = XIII\n| issue       = 2\n| pages       = 230\u2013236\n| via         =\n}}<ref name=\"The Nashville Tennessean 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = New Fiction and Books for Little Folks. | newspaper = [[The Tennessean|The Nashville Tennessean]] | location = [[Nashville, Tennessee]] | date = December 1, 1907 | page = 32 | url = https://www.newspapers.com/image/118994114/ | accessdate = February 3, 2019 | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | archive-url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27983823/new_fiction_and_books_for_little_folks/ | archive-date = February 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSpaid had planned to write a book on his nature studies, for which he had written notes and collected specimens.<ref name=\"Secrest 3\"/> However, in May 1917, he lost his home to a fire, which destroyed the notebooks containing his life's work in nature study.<ref name=\"Secrest 3\"/>\n\n== Death ==\nIn mid-February 1936, Spaid became ill while visiting his niece, Mrs. Lee Calvert, in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=\"The Morning News 1\"/> Two weeks later, he was taken to the home of his daughter, Margaret Spaid LaFollette, in [[Winchester, Virginia]].<ref name=\"The Morning News 1\"/> He suffered a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]] on 15&nbsp;March 1936<ref name=\"The Morning News 4\">{{cite newspaper | title = Professor A. R. Spaid Ill With Heart Attack | newspaper = [[The News Journal|Wilmington Morning News]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = March 16, 1936 | page = 4 | url = https://www.newspapers.com/image/154510752/ | accessdate = February 3, 2019 | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | archive-url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27985844/professor_a_r_spaid_ill_with_heart/ | archive-date = February 3, 2019}}</ref> and died of [[heart failure]] the following day.<ref name=\"The Morning News 1\"/> Spaid was survived by his wife and five children.<ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/> His funeral service was held at the Christian Church in Winchester on 19&nbsp;March 1936.<ref name=\"The Morning News 3\">{{cite newspaper | title = Prof. A. R. M. Spaid's Funeral | newspaper = [[The News Journal|Wilmington Morning News]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = March 18, 1936 | page = 4 | url = https://www.newspapers.com/image/154512418/ | accessdate = February 2, 2019 | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | archive-url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27959256/prof_a_r_m_spaids_funeral/ | archive-date = February 2, 2019}}</ref> Spaid was [[burial|interred]] at [[Mount Hebron Cemetery and Gatehouse|Mount Hebron Cemetery]] in Winchester. Spaid's obituary in the ''[[The News Journal|Wilmington Morning News]]'' wrote that he had \"devoted his life to educational work\".<ref name=\"The Morning News 1\"/>\n\n== Personal life ==\n=== Marriage and children ===\n[[File:Mrs. Mary Abi Spaid.jpg|thumb|right|Spaid's wife, Mary Abi Farquhar Spaid]]\nSpaid married Mary Abi Farquhar on September 30, 1897.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/><ref name=\"Secrest 3\"/> Farquhar was born on April 11, 1872 and was the daughter of Benjamin and Mary B. Farquhar of Wilmington, Ohio.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> She graduated from Wilmington College in June 1894, a year after Spaid.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/> Farquhar underwent training in a year-long kindergarten teaching class in [[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus]] and worked as a kindergarten teacher at the Alexis I. duPont School.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/> Spaid and his wife had six children, consisting of two daughters and four sons:<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/><ref name=\"Secrest 3\"/>\n* Arthur Farquhar Spaid (July 10, 1898 \u2013 November 12, 1989)<ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/>\n* Harold Blin Spaid (June 1, 1900 \u2013 May 27, 1903)\n* Charles Dalney Spaid (February 21, 1904 \u2013 August 7, 1949)<ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/><ref name=\"Clinton County Democrat 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Persons and Society. | newspaper = Clinton County Democrat | location = [[Wilmington, Ohio]] | date = August 2, 1917 | page = 4 | url = https://newspaperarchive.com/wilmington-clinton-county-democrat-aug-02-1917-p-4/ | accessdate = February 3, 2019 | via = [[NewspaperArchive.com]] | archive-url = https://newspaperarchive.com/other-articles-clipping-aug-02-1917-1024398/ | archive-date = February 3, 2019}}</ref>\n* Mary Margaret Spaid LaFollette (January 26, 1906 \u2013 June 26, 1965),<ref name=\"Clinton County Democrat 1\"/> married Russell Olin LaFollette<ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/>\n* Ralph Stirling Spaid (June 18, 1908 \u2013 January 21, 1976)<ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/>\n* Ruth Louise Spaid David (September 22, 1909 \u2013 April 16, 1983),<ref name=\"Clinton County Democrat 1\"/> married Miles David<ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/>\n\n=== Civic and religious affiliations ===\nIn April 1900, Spaid was a founding member and first president of the [[National Audubon Society|Delaware Audubon Society]], with \"its object being the protection of birds and the discouraging of their use in wearing apparel and for the purposes of ornament.\"<ref name=\"The Wilmington Daily Republican 2\">{{cite newspaper | title = Will Protect the Birds. | newspaper = The Wilmington Daily Republican | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = April 11, 1900 | page = 4 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_fidelius_ver01/data/sn88053055/00271741248/1900041101/0361.pdf | accessdate = September 14, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190914223852/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_fidelius_ver01/data/sn88053055/00271741248/1900041101/0361.pdf | archive-date = September 14, 2019}}</ref> He served as a state director of Delaware's [[National Education Association]] and was a member of the National Society for the Promotion of Vocational Education.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/><ref name=\"Secrest 3\"/> Spaid was also a member of the [[Ancient Order of United Workmen]], the [[National Grange of the Order of Patrons of Husbandry]], and the [[Methodist Episcopal Church]].<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/> He held offices in both the Ancient Order of United Workmen and the National Grange.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> While he resided in Wilmington, Delaware, Spaid was a member of the Washington Heights Methodist Episcopal Church,<ref name=\"Every Evening 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Washington Heights M. E. Church | newspaper = Every Evening\u2014Wilmington Daily Commercial | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = June 7, 1906 | page = 2 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn87062237/1906-06-07/ed-1/seq-2.pdf | accessdate = February 19, 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190219013155/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn87062237/1906-06-07/ed-1/seq-2.pdf | archive-date = February 19, 2019}}</ref> and one of the founders of the McCabe Memorial Methodist Episcopal Church.<ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/> He became a member of the [[American Museum of Natural History]] in 1935.<ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Delaware|Education|Maryland|Ohio|Virginia|West Virginia}}\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |title = Harloe\u2013Kelso Genealogy of the Descendants of John William Harloe and James Kelso, From the Beginning of Their Lineages in This Country to the Present Time, With a Number of Allied Families and Many Historical Facts |editor-last1 = Harloe |editor-first1 = Charles Bruce | editor-link1 =  |year = 1943 |publisher = Dr. Charles Bruce Harloe; Pifer Printing Company |location = [[Winchester, Virginia]] |isbn = | volume = |oclc = 192102027  |url = https://archive.org/details/harloekelsogenea00harl/\n |accessdate =  |ref = harv | via = [[Internet Archive]] }}\n* {{cite book |title = Haverford College Bulletin Graduate Register 1836\u20131904 |editor-last1 = Haverford College |editor-first1 = | editor-link1 = Haverford College |year = 1905 |publisher = [[Haverford College]] |location = [[Haverford, Pennsylvania]] |isbn = | volume = III | issue = 3 |oclc = 1048334043  |url = https://archive.org/details/listofgraduatesr00have/\n |accessdate =  |ref = harv | via = [[Internet Archive]] }}\n* {{cite book |title = History of Hampshire County, West Virginia From Its Earliest Settlement to the Present |last1 = Maxwell |first1 = Hu |authorlink1 = Hu Maxwell |last2 = Swisher |first2 = Howard Llewellyn |authorlink2 = Howard Llewellyn Swisher |year = 1897 |editor =  |publisher = A. Brown Boughner, Printer |location = [[Morgantown, West Virginia]] |isbn =  |oclc = 680931891 |page =  |pages =  |url = https://archive.org/details/historyofhampshi00maxw/ |accessdate =  |ref = harv | lastauthoramp = yes | via = [[Internet Archive]] }}\n* {{cite book |title = Spaid Genealogy from the First of the Name in This Country to the Present Time with A Number of Allied Families and Many Historical Facts |editor-last1 = Secrest |editor-first1 = Abraham Thompson |year = 1922 |publisher = Nitschke Brothers |location = [[Columbus, Ohio]] |isbn =  |oclc = 285160392 |page =  |pages =  |url = https://archive.org/details/spaidgenealogyfr00secr/\n |accessdate =  |ref = harv | via = [[Internet Archive]] }}\n* {{cite book |title = Biographical Catalogue of the Matriculates of Haverford College Together with Lists of the Members of the College Faculty and the Managers, Officers and Recipients of Honorary Degrees, 1833\u20131900 |editor-last1 = Thomas |editor-first1 = Allen C. |year = 1900 |publisher = Haverford College Alumni Association, Sherman and Company |location = Philadelphia |isbn = | volume = |oclc = 551359046  |url = https://archive.org/details/biographicalcata0have/\n |accessdate =  |ref = harv | via = [[Internet Archive]] }}\n* {{cite book |title = The United States: Its Beginnings, Progress and Modern Development |editor-last1 = Wiley |editor-first1 = Edwin |editor-last2 = Rines |editor-first2 = Irving E.  |year = 1913 |publisher = American Educational Alliance |location = New York |isbn =  |oclc = 12955408 |page =  |pages =  |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=uo4MAQAAMAAJ |volume = 7 |ref = harv | lastauthoramp = yes | via = [[Google Books]] }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spaid, Arthur R M}}\n[[Category:1866 births]]\n[[Category:1936 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:American academics]]\n[[Category:American librarians]]\n[[Category:American Methodists]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American school administrators]]\n[[Category:American school principals]]\n[[Category:American schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Educators from Delaware]]\n[[Category:Educators from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Educators from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Educators from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Educators from West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Haverford College alumni]]\n[[Category:Lecturers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Methodist Episcopal Church]]\n[[Category:National Education Association people]]\n[[Category:People associated with the American Museum of Natural History]]\n[[Category:People from Dorchester County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:People from Dover, Delaware]]\n[[Category:People from Hampshire County, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:People from New Castle County, Delaware]]\n[[Category:People from Rockingham County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:People from Salem, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:People from Washington Court House, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Salem University faculty]]\n[[Category:Wilmington College (Ohio) alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American educator, school administrator, lecturer, and writer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix =\n|name         = Arthur R. M. Spaid\n|honorific-suffix =\n|image        = Arthur R. M. Spaid.jpg\n|caption      = Portrait of Spaid from ''History of Hampshire County, West Virginia'' (1897)\n|alt          =\n|office = [[Delaware Department of Education|Delaware State Commissioner of Education]]\n|term_start   = 1 July 1917\n|term_end     = 1 July 1921\n|predecessor  =\n|successor    =\n|office2 = Superintendent of [[Dorchester County Public Schools]]\n|term_start2   = 1913\n|term_end2    = 1917\n|predecessor2  =\n|successor2   =\n|office3 = Superintendent of [[New Castle County, Delaware|New Castle County]] Public Schools\n|term_start3   = 1903\n|term_end3    = 1913\n|predecessor3  =\n|successor3   =\n|office4 = Principal of [[Alexis I. duPont High School]]\n|term_start4   = 1894\n|term_end4    = 1903\n|predecessor4  =\n|successor4   =\n|birth_date= {{Birth date|df=yes|1866|07|27}}\n|birth_place=[[Capon Springs, West Virginia]], United States\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|df=yes|1936|03|16|1866|07|27}}\n|death_place=[[Winchester, Virginia]], United States\n|resting_place=\n|alma_mater=[[Wilmington College (Ohio)|Wilmington College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|AB]])<br />[[Haverford College]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])<br />[[Columbia University]] (MA)\n|profession= [[educator]], school administrator, [[Superintendent (education)|superintendent]], and education commissioner\n|spouse= Mary Abi Farquhar Spaid\n|children=\n|relations=John W. Spaid (father)<br />Margaret Elizabeth Brill Spaid (mother)<ref name=\"The Washington Herald 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Woman of Seventy Expires. | newspaper = [[The Washington Herald]] | location = Washington, D.C. | date = 13 January 1910 | page = 9 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83045433/1910-01-13/ed-1/seq-9.pdf | accessdate = 20 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220220557/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83045433/1910-01-13/ed-1/seq-9.pdf | archive-date = 20 February 2019}}</ref>\n|residence=\n}}\n\n'''Arthur Rusmiselle Miller Spaid''' (27 July 1866 \u2013 16 March 1936) was an American educator, school administrator, lecturer, and writer. He served as principal of [[Alexis I. duPont High School]] (1894\u20131903) in [[Wilmington, Delaware]], superintendent of [[New Castle County, Delaware|New Castle County]] Public Schools (1903\u20131913) in Delaware, superintendent of [[Dorchester County Public Schools]] (1913\u20131917) in Maryland, and [[Delaware Department of Education|Delaware State commissioner of Education]] (1917\u20131921).\n\nIn 1894, Spaid relocated to Delaware, where he was elected principal of Alexis I. duPont High School in Wilmington and served in this position until 1903. Spaid became superintendent of New Castle County Public Schools in 1903 and remained in this position until 1913. Throughout his tenure as superintendent, Spaid argued for compulsory education and the consolidation of New Castle County's rural public schools. In response to a shortage of teachers, Spaid instituted pay raises for some teachers in July 1906 so that they would return for the fall term. In May 1908, the Delaware State Board of Education appointed Spaid and the county superintendents to a committee charged with revising the state public school system's curriculum.\n\nSpaid received a Master of Arts degree in education from [[Columbia University]] in 1917. In November 1918, he issued a bulletin entitled, ''Our Children Must Be Educated'', in which he appealed to parents and school administrators to address rising teacher resignations, withdrawals of school children and other conditions that affected the state's public school system. He stressed that it was necessary to keep Delaware's children in school to avoid illiteracy. Under Spaid's initiative to bring efficiency to the state's public school system, the Delaware State Board of Education adopted a new school code in 1919. In May 1921, Spaid and the State Board of Education urged county superintendents and school principals to observe [[Memorial Day]] at their schools. Spaid left Delaware in 1921 and engaged in [[Chautauqua]]-related work before becoming the head of the Education Department at [[Salem University]] in [[Salem, West Virginia]], from 1926 to 1936.\n\nSpaid was a [[Natural history|naturalist]] by hobby and took hundreds of photographs, using them to illustrate his nature study articles and lecture slides. Throughout his career as a school administrator, Spaid also served as an instructor, lecturer, and speaker for multiple courses, institutes, and organizations. Spaid was also an avid writer, and he published articles in ''[[Scientific American]]'' and ''[[Country Life in America]]''. Spaid had planned to author a book on his nature studies, for which he had written notes and collected specimens; however, his home and notebooks were destroyed in a fire in 1917. Spaid died at the home of his daughter in [[Winchester, Virginia]], in 1936. According to historians [[Hu Maxwell]] and [[Howard Llewellyn Swisher]], Spaid \"placed himself in the front rank of the educational works of Delaware, and received the commendation of the press and the educators for his advanced ideas.\"<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\">{{Harvnb|Maxwell|Swisher|1897|p=730.}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nArthur Rusmiselle Miller Spaid was born on 27&nbsp;July 1866 in [[Capon Springs, West Virginia|Capon Springs]], West Virginia, to John W. Spaid and his wife, Margaret Elizabeth Brill Spaid.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"Secrest 1\">{{Harvnb|Secrest|1922|p=65.}}</ref><ref name=\"The Morning News 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = A. R. M. Spaid Dies In Virginia; Once School Head Here | newspaper = [[The News Journal|Wilmington Morning News]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = 17 March 1936 | page = 1 | url = https://www.newspapers.com/image/154511419/ | accessdate = 4 November 2018 | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | archive-url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25098939/a_r_m_spaid_dies_in_virginia_once/ | archive-date = 4 November 2018}}</ref> Arthur Spaid was the eldest of six children, with two brothers and three sisters: Luther Lore \"Boyd\" Spaid (1868\u20131877), Elia May Spaid (1870\u20131911), Martha Evalona Spaid (1875\u20131921), William Pohe Spaid (1878\u20131885), and Eleanor \"Nellie\" Love Spaid (1881\u2013unknown).<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/> His great-great-grandfather, George Nicholas Spaid (n\u00e9 Spaht), originated from [[Kassel]], Germany, and settled in [[Hampshire County, West Virginia|Hampshire County]] along the [[Cacapon River]] in the late 18th century.<ref name=\"Maxwell 2\">{{Harvnb|Maxwell|Swisher|1897|p=729.}}</ref><ref name=\"Secrest 4\">{{Harvnb|Secrest|1922|pp=5\u20137.}}</ref> Spaid's parents raised their family on a small farm on [[Timber Ridge]].<ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/> His father was a [[Shoemaking|shoemaker]] who was interested in literature and recorded local history in notebooks.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/> \n\nSpaid received his primary and secondary education in the [[Hampshire County Schools|public schools of Hampshire County]] and worked on his family's farm until the age of 20.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\">{{cite newspaper | title = Delaware Men of Affairs | newspaper = [[The News Journal|The Evening Journal]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = 25 January 1919 | page = 14 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_hockessin_ver01/data/sn85042354/00383343033/1919012501/0900.pdf | accessdate = 14 September 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190914232942/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_hockessin_ver01/data/sn85042354/00383343033/1919012501/0900.pdf | archive-date = 14 September 2019}}</ref> He completed his primary education in 1886 and earned his teaching certificate shortly thereafter. In the spring of 1886, he attended Professor Taylor's private school in [[Lacey Spring, Virginia]], for three months and won prizes in spelling and history while there.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> Throughout his early education, Spaid was active in \"scholastic athletics,\" including corner ball, [[baseball]], running, and jumping.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> In the summer of 1886, Spaid briefly attended Professor Borglebaugh's [[normal school]] in nearby [[Broadway, Virginia]].<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/> He completed his teacher's examination shortly thereafter and earned his [[Certified teacher|teaching certificate]].<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/>\n\n== Career ==\n=== Teaching and librarian ===\nIn 1886, Spaid began his first teaching position at the rural Loan Oak School in Broadway; he remained there until 1887.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 2\">{{cite newspaper | title = A. R. M. Spaid Dies In Virginia; Once School Head Here | newspaper = [[The News Journal|Wilmington Morning News]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = 17 March 1936 | page = 2 | url = https://www.newspapers.com/image/154511438/ | accessdate = 2 February 2019 | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | archive-url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27954171/a_r_m_spaid_dies_in_virginia_once/ | archive-date = 2 February 2019}}</ref> During his time in Broadway, he was a member of the Broadway Literary Society.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> Spaid visited [[Washington Court House, Ohio|Washington, Ohio]], at his cousin's invitation.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/> He entered Washington College and subsequently resigned from his teaching position in Virginia.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/> To support himself during his first year in Washington, Spaid served as the college's assistant librarian and as the librarian of the town's [[Woman's Christian Temperance Union]] library.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/> During this time he lived on two to three dollars per month, and was a bachelor.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/> The following year, Spaid took on the role of the [[Sexton (office)|sexton]] of the Christian Church.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/>\n\n=== School administration ===\nFrom 1889 to 1890, Spaid served as the principal of [[Twin Township, Ross County, Ohio|Twin Township]] High School in [[Bourneville, Ohio]].<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/> From 1890 to 1891, he was principal of Bourneville's graded schools.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> While in Bourneville he economized by residing with village school teacher E. M. Parrett.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/> Spaid reentered college in 1891, but the illness and death of his brother-in-law Carter Gilbert Kelso caused him to return to Bourneville to complete Kelso's term at school.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name = \"Harloe 1\">{{Harvnb|Harloe|1943|p=222.}}</ref> After completing Kelso's term, Spaid returned to his studies, finished his course in 1893, and earned his [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree from [[Wilmington College (Ohio)|Wilmington College]] in [[Wilmington, Ohio]], where he was president of his class and participated in the Dorian Literary Society.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/>\n\nDuring his senior year at Wilmington College, Spaid was awarded the $500 Haverford Fellowship, which allowed him to pursue a year of post-graduate work at [[Haverford College]] in [[Haverford, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> He returned to [[Concord, Hampshire County, West Virginia|Concord]] in Hampshire County, West Virginia, and then entered Haverford College in 1893.<ref name=\"Thomas 1\">{{Harvnb|Thomas|1900|p=277.}}</ref> Spaid completed his graduate studies in American history and earned a [[Master of Arts]] degree from Haverford College in 1894.<ref name=\"The Morning News 1\"/><ref name=\"Thomas 1\"/><ref name=\"Haverford College 1\">{{Harvnb|Haverford College|1905|p=60.}}</ref>\n\nSpaid relocated to Delaware in 1894<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> and was elected principal of [[Alexis I. duPont High School]] in [[Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington]].<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/><ref name=\"Thomas 1\"/> According to historians [[Hu Maxwell]] and [[Howard Llewellyn Swisher]], Spaid \"placed himself in the front rank of the educational works of Delaware and received the commendation of the press and the educators for his advanced ideas.\"<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/> While serving as the high school's principal, he and his family resided in the Highlands neighborhood of Wilmington.<ref name=\"Thomas 1\"/> In June 1897, at the end of the school year, the school's students presented Spaid with a traveling case.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 8\">{{cite newspaper | title = Good-Bye School Days | newspaper = [[The News Journal|The Evening Journal]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = 24 June 1897 | page = 1 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_bear_ver01/data/sn85042354/00383343392/1897062401/0570.pdf | accessdate = 18 August 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190819020301/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_bear_ver01/data/sn85042354/00383343392/1897062401/0570.pdf | archive-date = 18 August 2019}}</ref> He served as the principal of Alexis I. duPont High School until 1903.<ref name=\"The Morning News 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/>\n\n=== Superintendent of county public schools ===\nSpaid was the Superintendent of [[New Castle County, Delaware|New Castle County]] Public Schools from 1903 to 1913.<ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> While serving as superintendent, he resided in [[Brandywine, Delaware|Brandywine]].<ref name=\"The Middletown Transcript 2\">{{cite newspaper | title = State Board of Education | newspaper = The Middletown Transcript | location = [[Middletown, Delaware]] | date = 19 November 1904 | page = 2 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84026820/1904-11-19/ed-1/seq-2.pdf | accessdate = 3 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190203230515/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84026820/1904-11-19/ed-1/seq-2.pdf | archive-date = 3 February 2019}}</ref> He was one of three county superintendents in Delaware; the other two administered the public schools in [[Kent County, Delaware|Kent]] and [[Sussex County, Delaware|Sussex]] counties.<ref name=\"The Middletown Transcript 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Consolidate Rural Schools | newspaper = The Middletown Transcript | location = [[Middletown, Delaware]] | date = 28 January 1905 | page = 2 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84026820/1905-01-28/ed-1/seq-2.pdf | accessdate = 3 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190203222016/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84026820/1905-01-28/ed-1/seq-2.pdf | archive-date = 3 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November 1904, a special session of the Delaware State Board of Education appointed Spaid and the other two county superintendents to a committee charged with proposing and explaining legislation to improve and modernize the state's public school system to the [[Delaware Senate]] and [[Delaware House of Representatives]].<ref name=\"The Middletown Transcript 2\"/> \n\nThroughout his tenure as superintendent, Spaid argued for compulsory education and the consolidation of the county's rural public schools. At a legislative conference on education in January 1905, Spaid and the other two county superintendents urged the consolidation of Delaware's rural schools to improve the education of students in the state's more isolated areas.<ref name=\"The Middletown Transcript 1\"/> Spaid declared at the conference that he would require greater influence if he were to be reappointed as superintendent.<ref name=\"The Middletown Transcript 1\"/> He stated that \"if the position of superintendent of free schools was not worth awarding on merit alone&nbsp;... then he wanted to get out.\"<ref name=\"The Middletown Transcript 1\"/> He emphasized the necessity for graded consolidated schools in rural areas of New Castle County.<ref name=\"The Middletown Transcript 1\"/> Spaid noted that some of the county's rural schools had only one student in attendance for weeks at a time during the school year, and because of this the county's public schools were wasting money and the children in those affected areas were growing up in \"ignorance\".<ref name=\"The Middletown Transcript 1\"/> Spaid concluded that \"compulsory education and consolidation of the schools was needed.\"<ref name=\"The Middletown Transcript 1\"/>\n\nIn response to a shortage of teachers, Spaid instituted pay raises for some teachers in July 1906 so they would return for the fall term.<ref name=\"Cecil Whig 2\">{{cite newspaper | title = News in Brief | newspaper = [[Cecil Whig]] | location = [[Elkton, Maryland]] | date = 28 July 1906 | page = 3 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83016348/1906-07-28/ed-1/seq-3.pdf | accessdate = 3 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190203212129/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83016348/1906-07-28/ed-1/seq-3.pdf | archive-date = 3 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nSpaid's support of [[Prohibition in the United States|prohibition]] brought him into conflict with Wilmington's [[German Americans|German American]] community.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 3\">{{cite newspaper | title = German Citizens Score Mr. Spaid | newspaper = [[The News Journal|The Evening Journal]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = 30 August 1907 | page = 6 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1907-08-30/ed-1/seq-6.pdf | accessdate = 20 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220144727/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1907-08-30/ed-1/seq-6.pdf | archive-date = 20 February 2019}}</ref> In 1907, Spaid received a letter from William J. Hogan who inquired about his position on prohibition.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 3\"/> According to Wilmington's German American community, Spaid's response to the letter made \"insulting remarks\" about the unreliability of immigrants who drank beer.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 3\"/> The local [[National German-American Alliance|German-American Alliance]] held a public meeting at a [[Turners|Turn Hall]] regarding Spaid's letter and addressed an open letter to him in which the alliance noted the academic achievements of Germans and the low literacy rates in prohibition states.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 3\"/>\n\nIn May 1908, the Delaware State Board of Education appointed Spaid and the county superintendents to a committee charged with revising the state public school system's curriculum.<ref name=\"Cecil Whig 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = News in Brief | newspaper = [[Cecil Whig]] | location = [[Elkton, Maryland]] | date = 23 May 1908 | page = 3 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83016348/1908-05-23/ed-1/seq-3.pdf | accessdate = 3 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190203211301/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83016348/1908-05-23/ed-1/seq-3.pdf | archive-date = 3 February 2019}}</ref> In 1913, Spaid was named superintendent of [[Dorchester County Public Schools]] in nearby [[Dorchester County, Maryland]].<ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/>\n\nIn July 1914, Spaid was elected Supervisor of [[Washington County, Maryland]], schools and assumed his duties in August 1914.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 10\">{{cite newspaper | title = New Place for Prof. Spaid. | newspaper = [[The News Journal|The Evening Journal]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = 24 July 1914 | page = 6 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_fairfax_ver01/data/sn85042354/00383343057/1914072401/1003.pdf | accessdate = 13 September 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190913200124/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_fairfax_ver01/data/sn85042354/00383343057/1914072401/1003.pdf | archive-date = 13 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nSpaid received a Master of Arts degree in education from [[Columbia University]] in 1917.<ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/> While at Columbia, Spaid completed a course in \"school administration and supervision\" and was a member of the university's Administration Club.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> In addition to his Master of Arts degree, Columbia also conferred upon Spaid the title of \"Superintendent of Schools\".<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/>\n\n=== State Commissioner of Delaware Education ===\n[[File:Delaware Men of Affairs.jpg|thumb|right|Sketch portrait of Spaid from ''The Evening Journal'' (1919).]]\nFrom 1&nbsp;July 1917 until 1&nbsp;July 1921, Spaid served as the [[Delaware Department of Education|Delaware State Commissioner of Education]],<ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> during which time he resided with his family at 241 North State Street in [[Dover, Delaware|Dover]].<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/><ref name=\"Newark Post 4\">{{cite newspaper | title = Personals | newspaper = [[Newark Post]] | location = [[Newark, Delaware]] | date = 28 May 1919 | page = 5 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1919-05-28/ed-1/seq-5.pdf | accessdate = 3 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190203204210/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1919-05-28/ed-1/seq-5.pdf | archive-date = 3 February 2019}}</ref> Philanthropist [[Pierre S. du Pont]] was secretary of the Delaware State Board of Education while Spaid served in this position.<ref name=\"Newark Post 7\">{{cite newspaper | title = State Board of Education Here Friday | newspaper = [[Newark Post]] | location = [[Newark, Delaware]] | date = 1 October 1919 | page = 8 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1919-10-01/ed-1/seq-8.pdf | accessdate = 20 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220175834/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1919-10-01/ed-1/seq-8.pdf | archive-date = 20 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1918, Spaid held meetings of the Delaware State Board of Education at [[Stanton, Delaware|Stanton]] and locations across Delaware to hear from residents in school districts affected by the [[Delaware General Assembly]]'s 1915 alteration of school district boundaries, to include consolidation of districts.<ref name=\"Newark Post 6\">{{cite newspaper | title = State Board Meeting at Stanton | newspaper = [[Newark Post]] | location = [[Newark, Delaware]] | date = 8 May 1918 | page = 5 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1918-05-08/ed-1/seq-5.pdf | accessdate = 20 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220170320/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1918-05-08/ed-1/seq-5.pdf | archive-date = 20 February 2019}}</ref> As state commissioner, he convened a State Teachers' Institute in [[Newark, Delaware|Newark]] in August 1918.<ref name=\"Newark Post 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Institute Closed Friday | newspaper = [[Newark Post]] | location = [[Newark, Delaware]] | date = 28 August 1918 | page = 1 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1918-08-28/ed-1/seq-1.pdf | accessdate = 3 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190203200528/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1918-08-28/ed-1/seq-1.pdf | archive-date = 3 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring his tenure as state commissioner, Delaware's public school system was impacted by [[World War I]] and the [[Spanish flu|1918 influenza pandemic]]. The pandemic caused Delaware's State Board of Health to shutter the state's public schools for three to four weeks.<ref name=\"Newark Post 5\">{{cite newspaper | title = Our Children Must Be Educated | newspaper = [[Newark Post]] | location = [[Newark, Delaware]] | date = 27 November 1918 | page = 7 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1918-11-27/ed-1/seq-7.pdf | accessdate = 3 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190203215056/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1918-11-27/ed-1/seq-7.pdf | archive-date = 3 February 2019}}</ref> In November 1918, Spaid issued a four-page bulletin entitled, ''Our Children Must Be Educated'', in which he appealed to parents and school administrators to address rising teacher resignations, school children withdrawals and other conditions affecting the state's public school system.<ref name=\"Newark Post 5\"/> In his bulletin, Spaid commended the work of [[Liberty bond]] campaigns and War Work drives.<ref name=\"Newark Post 5\"/> In addition, he stated, \"This great world war is being fought to make democracy safe, but a democracy to be safe must be composed of intelligent citizens.\"<ref name=\"Newark Post 5\"/> He stressed that it was necessary to keep Delaware's children in school to avoid illiteracy.<ref name=\"Newark Post 5\"/> He concluded his bulletin by stating, \"Let us make still one more 'drive,' and 'go over the top' for an efficient school system, thus laying the everlasting foundation of a government in which democracy will be safe.\"<ref name=\"Newark Post 5\"/>\n\nUnder Spaid's initiative to bring efficiency to the state's public school system, the Delaware State Board of Education adopted a new school code in 1919.<ref name=\"Newark Post 3\">{{cite newspaper | title = Commissioner of Education Explains Code | newspaper = [[Newark Post]] | location = [[Newark, Delaware]] | date = 2 July 1919 | page = 4 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1919-07-02/ed-1/seq-4.pdf | accessdate = 3 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190203201916/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1919-07-02/ed-1/seq-4.pdf | archive-date = 3 February 2019}}</ref> According to Spaid its purpose was to provide an equal education for all Delaware students.<ref name=\"Newark Post 3\"/> He also noted that the code addressed the problem of illiteracy, which had been discovered by [[draft board]]s during World War I,<ref name=\"Newark Post 3\"/> and that the code sought to integrate all of Delaware's public schools into a coordinated state system.<ref name=\"Newark Post 3\"/> In May 1921, Spaid and the State Board of Education urged county superintendents and school principals to observe [[Memorial Day]] at their schools, in coordination with local [[Grand Army of the Republic]], [[United Spanish War Veterans]], and [[World War Veterans]] organizations.<ref name=\"Newark Post 2\">{{cite newspaper | title = Asks Schools to Celebrate Memorial Day | newspaper = [[Newark Post]] | location = [[Newark, Delaware]] | date = 25 May 1921 | page = 3 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1921-05-25/ed-1/seq-3.pdf | accessdate = 3 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190203200455/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1921-05-25/ed-1/seq-3.pdf | archive-date = 3 February 2019}}</ref> Spaid and the state board also recommended that school children bring flowers from home, place them at veterans' graves in local cemeteries, and be dismissed for the remainder of the school day.<ref name=\"Newark Post 2\"/> Spaid resigned as Delaware's State Commissioner of Education in 1921.<ref name=\"Normal Instructor 1\">{{cite journal | title = Educational Notes | newspaper = Normal Instructor and Primary Plans | publisher = F.A. Owen Publishing Company | location = [[Dansville, Livingston County, New York|Dansville, New York]] | date = September 1921 | volume = XXX | issue = 9 | page = 16 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=H1M5AQAAMAAJ | accessdate = 16 February 2020 | via = [[Google Books]] }}</ref>\n\n=== Later years ===\nIn 1921, after resigning as Delaware's State Commissioner of Education, Spaid left Delaware and began engaging in [[Chautauqua]]-related work.<ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/> Around 1926, he became head of the Education Department at [[Salem University]] in [[Salem, West Virginia]], and served in this position until 1936.<ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/>\n\n== Lecturer and writer ==\nSpaid was a [[Natural history|naturalist]] by hobby.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/> He took hundreds of photographs of objects in nature, and used these photographs to illustrate his nature study articles and lecture slides.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/>\n\nThroughout his career as a school administrator, Spaid also served as an instructor, lecturer, and speaker for multiple courses, institutes, and organizations. In 1900 and 1902, Spaid delivered illustrated lectures for the Natural History Society of Delaware at the [[Wilmington Friends School]] on the topics of \"The Historic and Picturesque [[Shenandoah Valley]]\",<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Lectured on Shenandoah Valley | newspaper = [[The News Journal|The Evening Journal]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = 26 May 1900 | page = 4 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1900-05-26/ed-1/seq-4.pdf | accessdate = 4 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190204005407/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1900-05-26/ed-1/seq-4.pdf | archive-date = 4 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"The Wilmington Daily Republican 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Educational Matters. | newspaper = The Wilmington Daily Republican | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = 23 May 1900 | page = 4 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_fidelius_ver01/data/sn88053055/00271741248/1900052301/0509.pdf | accessdate = 13 September 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190913200558/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_fidelius_ver01/data/sn88053055/00271741248/1900052301/0509.pdf | archive-date = 13 September 2019}}</ref> \"Eggs and Feathers\",<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 7\">{{cite newspaper | title = Mr. Spaid to Lecture | newspaper = [[The News Journal|The Evening Journal]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = 9 January 1902 | page = 5 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1902-01-09/ed-1/seq-5.pdf | accessdate = 20 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220203506/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1902-01-09/ed-1/seq-5.pdf | archive-date = 20 February 2019}}</ref> and \"Leaves and Blossoms.\"<ref name=\"The Evening Republican 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Dots. | newspaper = The Evening Republican | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = 11 April 1902 | page = 1 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053043/1902-04-11/ed-1/seq-1.pdf | accessdate = 20 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220184703/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053043/1902-04-11/ed-1/seq-1.pdf | archive-date = 20 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 4\">{{cite newspaper | title = Local News Notes | newspaper = [[The News Journal|The Evening Journal]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = 2 April 1900 | page = 1 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1900-04-02/ed-1/seq-1.pdf | accessdate = 20 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220190415/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1900-04-02/ed-1/seq-1.pdf | archive-date = 20 February 2019}}</ref> In 1901, Spaid delivered a lecture on reptiles entitled \"Fangs, Fins and Stings\" in the [[Breck's Mill Area]] of Wilmington,<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 2\">{{cite newspaper | title = Lectured on Reptiles | newspaper = [[The News Journal|The Evening Journal]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = 16 November 1901 | page = 1 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1901-11-16/ed-1/seq-1.pdf | accessdate = 4 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190204014658/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1901-11-16/ed-1/seq-1.pdf | archive-date = 4 February 2019}}</ref> and in February and April 1904, he presented a lecture tour across northern Delaware with illustrated lectures on \"Eggs and Feathers\", \"The Picturesque Luray Caverns\", and \"Historic Shenandoah Valley.\"<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 5\">{{cite newspaper | title = Spaid to Lecture. | newspaper = [[The News Journal|The Evening Journal]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = 12 February 1904 | page = 3 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1904-02-12/ed-1/seq-3.pdf | accessdate = 20 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220190949/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1904-02-12/ed-1/seq-3.pdf | archive-date = 20 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 6\">{{cite newspaper | title = Lectures by Prof. Spaid. | newspaper = [[The News Journal|The Evening Journal]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = 11 April 1904 | page = 5 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1904-04-11/ed-1/seq-5.pdf | accessdate = 20 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220193059/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85042354/1904-04-11/ed-1/seq-5.pdf | archive-date = 20 February 2019}}</ref> Between 1903 and 1905, Spaid gave 100 lectures to around 10,000 people,<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 9\">{{cite newspaper | title = Gave Many Free Lectures. | newspaper = [[The News Journal|The Evening Journal]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = 31 July 1905 | page = 5 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_christiana_ver01/data/sn85042354/00383343513/1905073101/1182.pdf | accessdate = 13 September 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190913193734/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_christiana_ver01/data/sn85042354/00383343513/1905073101/1182.pdf | archive-date = 13 September 2019}}</ref> including a new lecture entitled, \"Delaware, Nesting Place of the Blue Hen's Chickens\".<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 9\"/> In April 1911, at a meeting of rural New Castle County teachers in Wilmington Spaid delivered a speech on birds.<ref name=\"Newark Post 8\">{{cite newspaper | title = County Teachers Entertained | newspaper = [[Newark Post]] | location = [[Newark, Delaware]] | date = 26 April 1911 | page = 3 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1911-04-26/ed-1/seq-3.pdf | accessdate = 20 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220194956/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1911-04-26/ed-1/seq-3.pdf | archive-date = 20 February 2019}}</ref> In November 1917, he addressed the annual convention of the Delaware Woman's Christian Temperance Union in [[Seaford, Delaware|Seaford]] on the importance of [[Department of Scientific Temperance Instruction|scientific temperance instruction]] in public schools.<ref name=\"The Union Signal 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Patriotism and Suffrage Live Topics at Delaware Convention | newspaper = The Union Signal | location = [[Evanston, Illinois]] | date = 15 November 1917 | page = 13 | url = https://archive.org/details/unionsignaljourn43woma/page/n705 | accessdate = 21 February 2019 | via = [[Internet Archive]] | archive-url = | archive-date = }}</ref> In June 1919, Spaid held an open-air meeting on faith and asserted that \"one outstanding result\" of World War I \"was a return to elemental Christian faith.\"<ref name=\"Newark Post 9\">{{cite newspaper | title = First Of Open Air Meetings Held Sunday Night | newspaper = [[Newark Post]] | location = [[Newark, Delaware]] | date = 18 June 1919 | page = 1 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1919-06-18/ed-1/seq-1.pdf | accessdate = 20 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220205623/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88053005/1919-06-18/ed-1/seq-1.pdf | archive-date = 20 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring his tenure as New Castle County superintendent, Spaid delivered 100 lectures in the county's schools.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> He was an instructor and lecturer for the Delaware State Summer School for 11 years, and for the Maryland State Summer School for two years.<ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/> He served as a Sunday speaker for the [[temperance movement]] [[Anti-Saloon League]] in Delaware, Maryland, New York, and Pennsylvania for several years.<ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/> In addition, Spaid was a lecturer in the People's Course at [[Newark, New Jersey]], for five years,<ref name=\"Secrest 1\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/> and was a lecturer at teachers' institutes in Delaware, Indiana, Maryland, New Jersey, Ohio, and Pennsylvania.<ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/><ref name=\"Secrest 2\">{{Harvnb|Secrest|1922|pp=65\u201366.}}</ref>\n\n=== Publications ===\nIn addition to public speaking, Spaid was an avid writer.<ref name=\"Secrest 3\">{{Harvnb|Secrest|1922|p=66.}}</ref> His articles on the subjects of history and nature included:<ref name=\"Secrest 3\"/>\n* {{cite magazine\n| date        = March\u2013August 1895\n| title       = Slavery in Pennsylvania\n| magazine    = The American Historical Register and Monthly Gazette of the Patriotic\u2013Hereditary Societies of the United States of America\n| location    = Philadelphia\n| publisher   = The Historical Register Publishing Company\n| oclc        = 565053224\n| volume      = ii\n| pages       = 1181\u20131187\n| url         = https://archive.org/details/americanhistoricv2brow/page/1180\n}}<ref name=\"The Record-Union 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = New Publications. | newspaper = [[The Sacramento Union|Sacramento Daily Record-Union]] | location = [[Sacramento, California]] | date = 12 July 1895 | page = 4 | url = https://www.newspapers.com/image/42201518/ | accessdate = 3 February 2019 | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | archive-url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27961540/new_publications/ | archive-date = 3 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"The Pittsburgh Post 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Slavery in Pennsylvania. | newspaper = [[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette#Post|The Pittsburgh Post]] | location = [[Pittsburgh]] | date = 14 July 1895 | page = 4 | url = https://www.newspapers.com/image/86406505/ | accessdate = 3 February 2019 | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | archive-url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27985609/slavery_in_pennsylvania/ | archive-date = 3 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Wiley 1\">{{Harvnb|Wiley|Rines|1913|p=168.}}</ref>\n* {{cite magazine\n| date        = 14 November 1903\n| title       = Some of Our Common Snakes.\u2014I.\n| magazine    = [[Scientific American]]\n| issn        = 0036-8733\n| pages       = 352\u2013353\n| volume      = 89\n| issue       = 20\n| publisher   = Munn and Company\n| location    = New York\n| url         = https://archive.org/details/scientific-american-1903-11-14/page/n17\n| via         =\n}}<ref name=\"Scientific American 1\">{{cite magazine\n |date         = 14 November 1903\n |title        = Some of Our Common Snakes.\u2014I.\n |magazine     = [[Scientific American]]\n |issn         = 0036-8733\n |pages        = 352\u2013353\n |volume       = 89\n |issue        = 20\n |publisher    = Munn and Company\n |location     = New York\n |url          = https://archive.org/details/scientific-american-1903-11-14/\n |via          = [[Internet Archive]]\n |access-date  = 21 February 2019\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170324021659/https://archive.org/details/scientific-american-1903-11-14\n |archive-date = 24 March 2017\n |url-status   = live\n}}</ref>\n* {{cite magazine\n| date        = 1904\n| title       = Harmless Little Reptile\n| magazine    = [[Scientific American]]\n| issn        = 0036-8733\n}}<ref name=\"The St. Tammany Farmer 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Harmless Little Reptile. | newspaper = The St. Tammany Farmer | location = [[Covington, Louisiana]] | date = 23 April 1904 | page = 6 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015387/1904-04-23/ed-1/seq-6.pdf | accessdate = 20 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220183147/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015387/1904-04-23/ed-1/seq-6.pdf | archive-date = 20 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Williston Graphic 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Harmless Little Reptile. | newspaper = Williston Graphic | location = [[Williston, North Dakota]] | date = 28 April 1904 | page = 6 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88076270/1904-04-28/ed-1/seq-6.pdf | accessdate = 20 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190220182302/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88076270/1904-04-28/ed-1/seq-6.pdf | archive-date = 20 February 2019}}</ref>\n* {{cite magazine\n| date        = December 1907\n| title       = Among the Holly Gatherers\n| url         = https://books.google.com/books?id=l4U3AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA230\n| magazine    = [[Country Life in America]]\n| location    = New York\n| publisher   = [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday, Page & Company]]\n| oclc        = 844607264\n| volume      = XIII\n| issue       = 2\n| pages       = 230\u2013236\n| via         =\n}}<ref name=\"The Nashville Tennessean 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = New Fiction and Books for Little Folks. | newspaper = [[The Tennessean|The Nashville Tennessean]] | location = [[Nashville, Tennessee]] | date = 1 December 1907 | page = 32 | url = https://www.newspapers.com/image/118994114/ | accessdate = 3 February 2019 | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | archive-url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27983823/new_fiction_and_books_for_little_folks/ | archive-date = 3 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nSpaid had planned to write a book on his nature studies, for which he had written notes and collected specimens.<ref name=\"Secrest 3\"/> However, in May 1917, he lost his home to a fire, which destroyed the notebooks containing his life's work in nature study.<ref name=\"Secrest 3\"/>\n\n== Death ==\nIn mid-February 1936, Spaid became ill while visiting his niece, Mrs. Lee Calvert, in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=\"The Morning News 1\"/> Two weeks later, he was taken to the home of his daughter, Margaret Spaid LaFollette, in [[Winchester, Virginia]].<ref name=\"The Morning News 1\"/> He suffered a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]] on 15&nbsp;March 1936<ref name=\"The Morning News 4\">{{cite newspaper | title = Professor A. R. Spaid Ill With Heart Attack | newspaper = [[The News Journal|Wilmington Morning News]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = 16 March 1936 | page = 4 | url = https://www.newspapers.com/image/154510752/ | accessdate = 3 February 2019 | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | archive-url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27985844/professor_a_r_spaid_ill_with_heart/ | archive-date = 3 February 2019}}</ref> and died of [[heart failure]] the following day.<ref name=\"The Morning News 1\"/> Spaid was survived by his wife and five children.<ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/> His funeral service was held at the Christian Church in Winchester on 19&nbsp;March 1936.<ref name=\"The Morning News 3\">{{cite newspaper | title = Prof. A. R. M. Spaid's Funeral | newspaper = [[The News Journal|Wilmington Morning News]] | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = 18 March 1936 | page = 4 | url = https://www.newspapers.com/image/154512418/ | accessdate = 2 February 2019 | via = [[Newspapers.com]] | archive-url = https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27959256/prof_a_r_m_spaids_funeral/ | archive-date = 2 February 2019}}</ref> Spaid was [[burial|interred]] at [[Mount Hebron Cemetery and Gatehouse|Mount Hebron Cemetery]] in Winchester. Spaid's obituary in the ''[[The News Journal|Wilmington Morning News]]'' wrote that he had \"devoted his life to educational work\".<ref name=\"The Morning News 1\"/>\n\n== Personal life ==\n=== Marriage and children ===\n[[File:Mrs. Mary Abi Spaid.jpg|thumb|right|Spaid's wife, Mary Abi Farquhar Spaid]]\nSpaid married Mary Abi Farquhar on 30 September 1897.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/><ref name=\"Secrest 3\"/> Farquhar was born on 11 April 1872 and was the daughter of Benjamin and Mary B. Farquhar of Wilmington, Ohio.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> She graduated from Wilmington College in June 1894, a year after Spaid.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/> Farquhar underwent training in a year-long kindergarten teaching class in [[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus]] and worked as a kindergarten teacher at the Alexis I. duPont School.<ref name=\"Maxwell 1\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/> Spaid and his wife had six children, consisting of two daughters and four sons:<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/><ref name=\"Secrest 3\"/>\n* Arthur Farquhar Spaid (10 July 1898 \u2013 12 November 1989)<ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/>\n* Harold Blin Spaid (1 June 1900 \u2013 27 May 1903)\n* Charles Dalney Spaid (21 February 1904 \u2013 7 August 1949)<ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/><ref name=\"Clinton County Democrat 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Persons and Society. | newspaper = Clinton County Democrat | location = [[Wilmington, Ohio]] | date = 2 August 1917 | page = 4 | url = https://newspaperarchive.com/wilmington-clinton-county-democrat-aug-02-1917-p-4/ | accessdate = 3 February 2019 | via = [[NewspaperArchive.com]] | archive-url = https://newspaperarchive.com/other-articles-clipping-aug-02-1917-1024398/ | archive-date = 3 February 2019}}</ref>\n* Mary Margaret Spaid LaFollette (26 January 1906 \u2013 26 June 1965),<ref name=\"Clinton County Democrat 1\"/> married Russell Olin LaFollette<ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/>\n* Ralph Stirling Spaid (18 June 1908 \u2013 21 January 1976)<ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/>\n* Ruth Louise Spaid David (22 September 1909 \u2013 16 April 1983),<ref name=\"Clinton County Democrat 1\"/> married Miles David<ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/>\n\n=== Civic and religious affiliations ===\nIn April 1900, Spaid was a founding member and first president of the [[National Audubon Society|Delaware Audubon Society]], with \"its object being the protection of birds and the discouraging of their use in wearing apparel and for the purposes of ornament.\"<ref name=\"The Wilmington Daily Republican 2\">{{cite newspaper | title = Will Protect the Birds. | newspaper = The Wilmington Daily Republican | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = 11 April 1900 | page = 4 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_fidelius_ver01/data/sn88053055/00271741248/1900041101/0361.pdf | accessdate = 14 September 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190914223852/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/data/batches/deu_fidelius_ver01/data/sn88053055/00271741248/1900041101/0361.pdf | archive-date = 14 September 2019}}</ref> He served as a state director of Delaware's [[National Education Association]] and was a member of the National Society for the Promotion of Vocational Education.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/><ref name=\"Secrest 3\"/> Spaid was also a member of the [[Ancient Order of United Workmen]], the [[National Grange of the Order of Patrons of Husbandry]], and the [[Methodist Episcopal Church]].<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/><ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/> He held offices in both the Ancient Order of United Workmen and the National Grange.<ref name=\"The Evening Journal 11\"/> While he resided in Wilmington, Delaware, Spaid was a member of the Washington Heights Methodist Episcopal Church,<ref name=\"Every Evening 1\">{{cite newspaper | title = Washington Heights M. E. Church | newspaper = Every Evening\u2014Wilmington Daily Commercial | location = [[Wilmington, Delaware]] | date = 7 June 1906 | page = 2 | url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn87062237/1906-06-07/ed-1/seq-2.pdf | accessdate = 19 February 2019 | via = [[Chronicling America]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190219013155/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn87062237/1906-06-07/ed-1/seq-2.pdf | archive-date = 19 February 2019}}</ref> and one of the founders of the McCabe Memorial Methodist Episcopal Church.<ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/> He became a member of the [[American Museum of Natural History]] in 1935.<ref name=\"The Morning News 2\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Delaware|Education|Maryland|Ohio|Virginia|West Virginia}}\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |title = Harloe\u2013Kelso Genealogy of the Descendants of John William Harloe and James Kelso, From the Beginning of Their Lineages in This Country to the Present Time, With a Number of Allied Families and Many Historical Facts |editor-last1 = Harloe |editor-first1 = Charles Bruce | editor-link1 =  |year = 1943 |publisher = Dr. Charles Bruce Harloe; Pifer Printing Company |location = [[Winchester, Virginia]] |isbn = | volume = |oclc = 192102027  |url = https://archive.org/details/harloekelsogenea00harl/\n |accessdate =  |ref = harv | via = [[Internet Archive]] }}\n* {{cite book |title = Haverford College Bulletin Graduate Register 1836\u20131904 |editor-last1 = Haverford College |editor-first1 = | editor-link1 = Haverford College |year = 1905 |publisher = [[Haverford College]] |location = [[Haverford, Pennsylvania]] |isbn = | volume = III | issue = 3 |oclc = 1048334043  |url = https://archive.org/details/listofgraduatesr00have/\n |accessdate =  |ref = harv | via = [[Internet Archive]] }}\n* {{cite book |title = History of Hampshire County, West Virginia From Its Earliest Settlement to the Present |last1 = Maxwell |first1 = Hu |authorlink1 = Hu Maxwell |last2 = Swisher |first2 = Howard Llewellyn |authorlink2 = Howard Llewellyn Swisher |year = 1897 |editor =  |publisher = A. Brown Boughner, Printer |location = [[Morgantown, West Virginia]] |isbn =  |oclc = 680931891 |page =  |pages =  |url = https://archive.org/details/historyofhampshi00maxw/ |accessdate =  |ref = harv | lastauthoramp = yes | via = [[Internet Archive]] }}\n* {{cite book |title = Spaid Genealogy from the First of the Name in This Country to the Present Time with A Number of Allied Families and Many Historical Facts |editor-last1 = Secrest |editor-first1 = Abraham Thompson |year = 1922 |publisher = Nitschke Brothers |location = [[Columbus, Ohio]] |isbn =  |oclc = 285160392 |page =  |pages =  |url = https://archive.org/details/spaidgenealogyfr00secr/\n |accessdate =  |ref = harv | via = [[Internet Archive]] }}\n* {{cite book |title = Biographical Catalogue of the Matriculates of Haverford College Together with Lists of the Members of the College Faculty and the Managers, Officers and Recipients of Honorary Degrees, 1833\u20131900 |editor-last1 = Thomas |editor-first1 = Allen C. |year = 1900 |publisher = Haverford College Alumni Association, Sherman and Company |location = Philadelphia |isbn = | volume = |oclc = 551359046  |url = https://archive.org/details/biographicalcata0have/\n |accessdate =  |ref = harv | via = [[Internet Archive]] }}\n* {{cite book |title = The United States: Its Beginnings, Progress and Modern Development |editor-last1 = Wiley |editor-first1 = Edwin |editor-last2 = Rines |editor-first2 = Irving E.  |year = 1913 |publisher = American Educational Alliance |location = New York |isbn =  |oclc = 12955408 |page =  |pages =  |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=uo4MAQAAMAAJ |volume = 7 |ref = harv | lastauthoramp = yes | via = [[Google Books]] }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spaid, Arthur R M}}\n[[Category:1866 births]]\n[[Category:1936 d